{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T23:34:01.937500", "agent_name": "PerfectRAG", "method_name": "load_cached_research", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "Cached research loaded from: perfect_rag/Threonine.md", "user_message": "Config: perfect_rag", "raw_response": "# Prebiotic Synthesis of L-Threonine: Comprehensive Literature Review\n\n## 1. Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\n\nTwo experimentally demonstrated pathways produce L-threonine (C4H9NO3, SMILES: CC(C(C(=O)O)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8), MW: 119.12) from prebiotically available precursors. These span surface and hydrothermal environments.\n\n### Pathway 1: Cyanosulfidic Nitrile Hydrolysis via Lactaldehyde Cyanohydrin (Surface Environment)\n\nThe cyanosulfidic protometabolism pathway demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) constructs L-threonine through a 3-step sequence starting from **lactaldehyde** and **hydrogen cyanide**, proceeding through a cyanohydrin intermediate and an aminonitrile intermediate. This pathway follows the general cyanosulfidic strategy: an aldehyde undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN, amination with ammonia displaces the hydroxyl to form an aminonitrile, and final nitrile hydrolysis yields the amino acid.\n\n**Step 1**: Lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 Cyanohydrin intermediate (Cyanohydrin formation)\n- SMILES: CC(O)C=O.C#N>>CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- Reactants: Lactaldehyde (C3H6O2, SMILES: CC(C=O)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3, MW: 74.08) + Hydrogen cyanide (CHN, SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H, MW: 27.03)\n- Product: Cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2, SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c1-4(7)2-5(8)3-6/h4-5,7-8H,2H2,1H3, MW: 115.06)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the aldehyde carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde. The cyanide ion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of the aldehyde, and subsequent protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani-type cyanohydrin reaction that extends the carbon chain by one carbon unit while introducing a nitrile functional group. Lactaldehyde is a plausible prebiotic C3 aldol product available from cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n\n**Step 2**: Cyanohydrin intermediate + NH3 \u2192 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + H2O (Aminonitrile formation)\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N.N>>CC(O)C(N)C#N.O\n- Reactants: Cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2, SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N) + Ammonia (H3N, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3, MW: 17.03)\n- Products: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3, MW: 100.12) + H2O (SMILES: O)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement of the carbon skeleton to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.\n\n**Step 3**: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Threonine + NH3 (Nitrile hydrolysis)\n- SMILES: CC(O)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(O)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Reactants: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O) + 2 H2O (SMILES: O)\n- Products: L-Threonine (C4H9NO3, SMILES: CC(C(C(=O)O)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8), MW: 119.12) + Ammonia (H3N, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of water to the nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide), followed by further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia (NH3). This is the final step of the general cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid pathway, converting the C\u2261N triple bond to a carboxylic acid via stepwise hydration.\n\nThis three-step sequence is part of the broader Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry framework, in which HCN-derived nitriles serve as amino acid precursors via hydrolysis under wet-dry cycling or UV-irradiated surface pool conditions. The same paper demonstrates that this unified chemistry produces precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids from simple feedstocks. The threonine pathway parallels the serine pathway (glycolaldehyde + HCN) but uses lactaldehyde as the starting aldehyde, introducing the methyl branch that distinguishes threonine from serine.\n\n### Pathway 2: Aldol Condensation of L-Alanine with Formaldehyde (Hydrothermal Environment)\n\nAubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, DOI: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2) demonstrated that **L-alanine** (C3H7NO2, SMILES: CC(C(=O)O)N, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6), MW: 89.09) reacts with **formaldehyde** (CH2O, SMILES: C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2, MW: 30.03) to produce L-threonine under submarine hydrothermal conditions.\n\n**Reaction**: L-Alanine + Formaldehyde \u2192 L-Threonine\n- SMILES: C[C@H](N)C(=O)O.C=O>>C[C@@H](O)[C@H](N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Hydrothermal (submarine hydrothermal systems)\n- Conditions: Elevated temperature and pressure characteristic of submarine hydrothermal vents\n- Mechanism: Aldol-type condensation \u2014 the alpha-carbon of L-alanine attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a hydroxymethyl group (-CH(OH)-). This converts the C3 amino acid (alanine) into the C4 amino acid (threonine) by extending the carbon skeleton by one carbon unit. Formaldehyde is a key C1 electrophile that is abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids from reduction of CO2 and Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.\n\nThis pathway links threonine synthesis to L-alanine, which is itself produced by multiple prebiotic routes including: (a) reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine in the presence of iron (Muchowska et al., 2019), (b) hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015), and (c) reduction of L-serine under hydrothermal conditions (Aubrey et al., 2008). The reaction is directly analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation demonstrated by the same research group, but applied one carbon unit higher in the amino acid homologous series.\n\n## 2. Key Intermediates and Precursors\n\n### Hub Molecule: L-Alanine (C3H7NO2)\n- Formula: C3H7NO2\n- SMILES: CC(C(=O)O)N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\n- MW: 89.09\n- Role: **Key amino acid precursor for Pathway 2** \u2014 L-alanine is the substrate for the aldol condensation with formaldehyde that produces threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008). Alanine is itself produced by multiple prebiotic routes: reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine using iron catalysts at 70\u00b0C (Muchowska et al., 2019), hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015), and reduction of L-serine under hydrothermal conditions (Aubrey et al., 2008). Alanine is one of the most abundant amino acids produced in prebiotic chemistry experiments.\n\n### Key Intermediate: Cyanohydrin Intermediate (C5H9NO2)\n- Formula: C5H9NO2\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c1-4(7)2-5(8)3-6/h4-5,7-8H,2H2,1H3\n- MW: 115.06\n- Role: **Cyanohydrin intermediate in Pathway 1** \u2014 formed by nucleophilic addition of HCN to lactaldehyde. This intermediate is the direct precursor to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile via amination with ammonia. Represents the carbon skeleton that will become threonine after amination and hydrolysis.\n\n### Key Intermediate: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O)\n- Formula: C4H8N2O\n- SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\n- MW: 100.12\n- Role: **Aminonitrile intermediate in Pathway 1** \u2014 formed by amination of the cyanohydrin intermediate with ammonia. This is the direct Strecker-type aminonitrile precursor of threonine, bearing the complete C4 carbon skeleton with the beta-hydroxy group and alpha-amino group in the correct positions. Hydrolysis of the nitrile group yields threonine.\n\n### Other Key Molecules\n\n**Lactaldehyde** (C3H6O2)\n- Formula: C3H6O2\n- SMILES: CC(C=O)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\n- MW: 74.08\n- Role: Starting aldehyde for Pathway 1 \u2014 undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN to initiate the cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis. Lactaldehyde is a C3 hydroxy aldehyde that is prebiotically plausible as a product of aldol chemistry and sugar photochemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions.\n\n**Hydrogen Cyanide** (CHN)\n- Formula: CHN\n- SMILES: C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- MW: 27.03\n- Role: Key C1 nucleophile for cyanohydrin formation in Pathway 1. HCN is a central feedstock in cyanosulfidic chemistry, produced by photochemistry of N2/CH4 atmospheres, impact synthesis, and volcanic outgassing. It provides the carbon and nitrogen atoms that ultimately become the carboxylate group of threonine after hydrolysis.\n\n**Formaldehyde** (CH2O)\n- Formula: CH2O\n- SMILES: C=O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\n- MW: 30.03\n- Role: Key C1 electrophile for Pathway 2 \u2014 reacts with L-alanine via aldol condensation to produce threonine. Formaldehyde is a common prebiotic starting molecule produced by photoreduction of CO2, hydrothermal reduction of CO2, Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on mineral surfaces, and UV photolysis of methane.\n\n### Starting Molecules\n- **H2O**: SMILES: O, InChI: InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\n- **NH3** (ammonia): SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\n- **HCN** (hydrogen cyanide): SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- **H2CO** (formaldehyde): SMILES: C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\n\n## 3. Reaction Mechanisms and Conditions\n\n### Reactions Producing Intermediates (Upstream)\n\n**Reaction U1: HCN cyanohydrin addition to lactaldehyde**\n- Lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 Cyanohydrin intermediate\n- SMILES: CC(O)C=O.C#N>>CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of lactaldehyde, forming a cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani reaction that extends the carbon chain by one unit. The reaction proceeds under mild aqueous conditions typical of cyanosulfidic surface chemistry.\n\n**Reaction U2: Aminonitrile formation from cyanohydrin + ammonia**\n- Cyanohydrin intermediate + NH3 \u2192 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + H2O\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N.N>>CC(O)C(N)C#N.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement of the carbon skeleton to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.\n\n### Reactions Producing L-Threonine (Final Steps)\n\n**Reaction F1: Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile**\n- 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Threonine + NH3\n- SMILES: CC(O)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(O)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide), which further hydrolyzes to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia. This is the terminal step of the general Strecker/cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid conversion.\n\n**Reaction F2: Aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde**\n- L-Alanine + Formaldehyde \u2192 L-Threonine\n- SMILES: C[C@H](N)C(=O)O.C=O>>C[C@@H](O)[C@H](N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Hydrothermal (submarine hydrothermal systems)\n- Conditions: Elevated temperature and pressure\n- Source: Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008), *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, DOI: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2\n- Mechanism: Aldol condensation \u2014 the alpha-carbon of L-alanine attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a beta-hydroxyl group. This extends the C3 amino acid (alanine) to the C4 amino acid (threonine). The reaction is analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation from the same study.\n\n## 4. Mineral Catalysts and Surfaces\n\nThe threonine synthesis reactions described in the literature do not require specific mineral catalysts. However, the following environmental agents and conditions are relevant:\n\n- **Cyanosulfidic conditions** (Pathway 1): The Patel et al. (2015) reactions operate under the cyanosulfidic chemistry framework, which involves hydrogen cyanide (HCN), hydrogen sulfide (H2S), and UV irradiation in surface pools. While no specific mineral catalysts are documented for the threonine-specific reactions, the broader cyanosulfidic network utilizes phosphate minerals for phosphorylation and UV light as an energy source.\n\n- **Hydrothermal mineral surfaces** (Pathway 2): The Aubrey et al. (2008) aldol condensation operates under submarine hydrothermal conditions. While no specific mineral catalyst is documented for the alanine-formaldehyde condensation itself, the hydrothermal environment provides elevated temperatures and mineral surfaces (e.g., iron-sulfide minerals, clay minerals) that may facilitate the reaction. Additionally, the upstream production of L-alanine via reductive amination of pyruvate requires **Elemental Iron** (Fe\u2070) and **ferrous iron** (Fe\u00b2\u207a) as catalysts (Muchowska et al., 2019).\n\n- **Ultraviolet radiation**: UV photons (200-300 nm) from the young Sun drive the cyanosulfidic photochemistry that generates the feedstocks (HCN, lactaldehyde) for Pathway 1.\n\n## 5. Experimental Evidence\n\n### Study 1: Patel et al. (2015)\n- **Title**: \"Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism\"\n- **Journal**: Nature Chemistry\n- **DOI**: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- **Key finding**: Demonstrated that a unified cyanosulfidic chemistry starting from HCN and H2S can produce precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids. For threonine specifically, the paper describes a three-step pathway: (1) HCN cyanohydrin addition to lactaldehyde produces a cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2), (2) amination with ammonia converts the cyanohydrin to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O), and (3) nitrile hydrolysis yields L-threonine with release of ammonia. This is the cyanosulfidic analog of the Strecker synthesis, where the starting aldehyde (lactaldehyde) determines the amino acid product (threonine). The same framework produces glycine (from formaldehyde), alanine (from acetaldehyde), serine (from glycolaldehyde), and valine (from dihydroxyacetone-derived acetone), demonstrating a unified chemical origin for the amino acid repertoire.\n\n### Study 2: Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008)\n- **Title**: \"The Role of Submarine Hydrothermal Systems in the Synthesis of Amino Acids\"\n- **Journal**: Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres\n- **DOI**: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2\n- **Key finding**: Investigated amino acid synthesis under simulated submarine hydrothermal vent conditions. Demonstrated that L-alanine reacts with formaldehyde to produce L-threonine via aldol condensation. This reaction extends the carbon skeleton of a simpler amino acid (alanine, C3) to a more complex one (threonine, C4) by incorporating a C1 unit (formaldehyde). The same study demonstrated the analogous glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation, as well as serine reduction to alanine. These reactions establish a hydrothermal amino acid interconversion network where simpler amino acids serve as building blocks for more complex ones through aldol chemistry with formaldehyde.\n\n## 6. Environmental Context\n\n### Surface Environment (Primary for Pathway 1)\nThe cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015) operates under surface conditions:\n- **Cyanosulfidic nitrile chemistry**: Lactaldehyde reacts with HCN to form a cyanohydrin, which is aminated by ammonia and then hydrolyzed to threonine. This operates in surface pools where HCN-derived chemistry (UV-driven, evaporitic) produces aminonitrile intermediates that hydrolyze in wet phases.\n- **UV irradiation**: The young Sun provided intense UV flux (lacking an ozone shield), driving the photochemistry that generates HCN and other cyanosulfidic feedstocks.\n- **Wet-dry cycling**: Evaporitic pools undergo wet-dry cycles that concentrate reactants and drive condensation reactions, facilitating the cyanohydrin formation and amination steps.\n- **Temperature**: 300-370 K (ambient to warm surface conditions), compatible with the aqueous chemistry described.\n\n### Hydrothermal Environment (Primary for Pathway 2)\nThe aldol condensation pathway (Aubrey et al., 2008) operates under submarine hydrothermal conditions:\n- **L-Alanine availability**: L-alanine is produced by iron-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate at 70\u00b0C (Muchowska et al., 2019), by reduction of L-serine (Aubrey et al., 2008), and by cyanosulfidic aminonitrile hydrolysis (Patel et al., 2015). Multiple upstream pathways feed alanine into the hydrothermal environment.\n- **Formaldehyde availability**: Formaldehyde is produced by hydrothermal reduction of CO2 and by Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on native iron and nickel-iron mineral surfaces. It is a key C1 building block abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids.\n- **Temperature**: Elevated temperatures (350-600 K) characteristic of submarine hydrothermal vents drive the aldol condensation.\n\n### Environmental Interconnection\nThe threonine synthesis network exhibits cross-environment flow:\n1. **Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal**: L-Alanine produced by cyanosulfidic chemistry (Pathway 1-type aminonitrile hydrolysis in surface pools) could be transported to hydrothermal environments, where it undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde (Pathway 2).\n2. **Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface**: Alanine and formaldehyde generated at hydrothermal vents could be transported to surface environments via ocean circulation.\n3. **Parallel independent routes**: The two pathways operate independently in different environments (surface cyanosulfidic vs. hydrothermal aldol), providing robustness to the prebiotic threonine synthesis network.\n4. **Both \u2192 Biochemical**: Threonine produced by either pathway enters the prebiotic amino acid pool available for peptide bond formation, and serves as a precursor for further biochemical assembly. Threonine itself can thermally decompose to glycine under hydrothermal conditions (Vallentyne, 1964; Bada et al., 1978), linking it to the broader amino acid recycling network.\n\n## 7. Open Questions and Challenges\n\n1. **Chirality**: Both demonstrated prebiotic routes produce racemic threonine (equal L and D forms). The origin of homochirality (biological preference for L-amino acids) remains unresolved. Mineral surface adsorption, photolysis with circularly polarized light, or amplification through autocatalytic crystallization have been proposed but not demonstrated specifically for threonine.\n\n2. **Lactaldehyde availability**: Pathway 1 requires lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropionaldehyde), whose prebiotic abundance and stability are debated. It could form from aldol chemistry of simpler aldehydes (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde), from sugar photochemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions, or from reduction of pyruvaldehyde. Quantitative constraints on its steady-state concentration in surface environments are needed.\n\n3. **Threonine thermal stability**: Threonine is thermally labile and decomposes to glycine under hydrothermal conditions (Vallentyne, 1964; Bada et al., 1978). The balance between threonine production (via aldol condensation, Pathway 2) and thermal decomposition at hydrothermal temperatures is a key kinetic question. The retro-aldol decomposition of threonine to glycine (the reverse of the serine-type aldol reaction) may limit threonine accumulation in hydrothermal systems.\n\n4. **2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile stability**: Pathway 1 requires this aminonitrile intermediate to persist long enough for hydrolysis. Its stability under UV irradiation, varying pH, and temperature fluctuations in surface pools needs further study. Competing reactions (polymerization, reaction with other HCN-derived species) could reduce yields.\n\n5. **Formaldehyde concentration**: Pathway 2 requires formaldehyde, which is volatile and reactive. Its prebiotic concentration in hydrothermal environments is debated. Mineral adsorption, continuous production from CO2 reduction via serpentinization-derived H2, and thermophoretic concentration may maintain sufficient steady-state levels.\n\n6. **Alanine as precursor**: Pathway 2 requires L-alanine as a substrate, which must itself be produced by upstream prebiotic reactions. The availability of alanine in sufficient concentrations at hydrothermal vents, where it is simultaneously being consumed by aldol condensation and potentially decomposed at high temperatures, represents a kinetic bottleneck that needs quantitative modeling.\n\n7. **Selectivity and side products**: The aldol condensation of alanine with formaldehyde (Pathway 2) could potentially produce other isomeric products besides threonine. The stereoselectivity and regioselectivity of this reaction under prebiotic conditions, and the relative yields of threonine versus allo-threonine or other isomers, need further characterization.\n", "parsed_response": {"source": "perfect_rag/Threonine.md", "config": "perfect_rag", "length": 22083}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 0.0, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T23:34:01.938573", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Threonine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n# Prebiotic Synthesis of L-Threonine: Comprehensive Literature Review\n\n## 1. Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\n\nTwo experimentally demonstrated pathways produce L-threonine (C4H9NO3, SMILES: CC(C(C(=O)O)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8), MW: 119.12) from prebiotically available precursors. These span surface and hydrothermal environments.\n\n### Pathway 1: Cyanosulfidic Nitrile Hydrolysis via Lactaldehyde Cyanohydrin (Surface Environment)\n\nThe cyanosulfidic protometabolism pathway demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) constructs L-threonine through a 3-step sequence starting from **lactaldehyde** and **hydrogen cyanide**, proceeding through a cyanohydrin intermediate and an aminonitrile intermediate. This pathway follows the general cyanosulfidic strategy: an aldehyde undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN, amination with ammonia displaces the hydroxyl to form an aminonitrile, and final nitrile hydrolysis yields the amino acid.\n\n**Step 1**: Lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 Cyanohydrin intermediate (Cyanohydrin formation)\n- SMILES: CC(O)C=O.C#N>>CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- Reactants: Lactaldehyde (C3H6O2, SMILES: CC(C=O)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3, MW: 74.08) + Hydrogen cyanide (CHN, SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H, MW: 27.03)\n- Product: Cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2, SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c1-4(7)2-5(8)3-6/h4-5,7-8H,2H2,1H3, MW: 115.06)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the aldehyde carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde. The cyanide ion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of the aldehyde, and subsequent protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani-type cyanohydrin reaction that extends the carbon chain by one carbon unit while introducing a nitrile functional group. Lactaldehyde is a plausible prebiotic C3 aldol product available from cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n\n**Step 2**: Cyanohydrin intermediate + NH3 \u2192 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + H2O (Aminonitrile formation)\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N.N>>CC(O)C(N)C#N.O\n- Reactants: Cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2, SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N) + Ammonia (H3N, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3, MW: 17.03)\n- Products: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3, MW: 100.12) + H2O (SMILES: O)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement of the carbon skeleton to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.\n\n**Step 3**: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Threonine + NH3 (Nitrile hydrolysis)\n- SMILES: CC(O)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(O)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Reactants: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O) + 2 H2O (SMILES: O)\n- Products: L-Threonine (C4H9NO3, SMILES: CC(C(C(=O)O)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8), MW: 119.12) + Ammonia (H3N, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of water to the nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide), followed by further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia (NH3). This is the final step of the general cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid pathway, converting the C\u2261N triple bond to a carboxylic acid via stepwise hydration.\n\nThis three-step sequence is part of the broader Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry framework, in which HCN-derived nitriles serve as amino acid precursors via hydrolysis under wet-dry cycling or UV-irradiated surface pool conditions. The same paper demonstrates that this unified chemistry produces precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids from simple feedstocks. The threonine pathway parallels the serine pathway (glycolaldehyde + HCN) but uses lactaldehyde as the starting aldehyde, introducing the methyl branch that distinguishes threonine from serine.\n\n### Pathway 2: Aldol Condensation of L-Alanine with Formaldehyde (Hydrothermal Environment)\n\nAubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, DOI: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2) demonstrated that **L-alanine** (C3H7NO2, SMILES: CC(C(=O)O)N, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6), MW: 89.09) reacts with **formaldehyde** (CH2O, SMILES: C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2, MW: 30.03) to produce L-threonine under submarine hydrothermal conditions.\n\n**Reaction**: L-Alanine + Formaldehyde \u2192 L-Threonine\n- SMILES: C[C@H](N)C(=O)O.C=O>>C[C@@H](O)[C@H](N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Hydrothermal (submarine hydrothermal systems)\n- Conditions: Elevated temperature and pressure characteristic of submarine hydrothermal vents\n- Mechanism: Aldol-type condensation \u2014 the alpha-carbon of L-alanine attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a hydroxymethyl group (-CH(OH)-). This converts the C3 amino acid (alanine) into the C4 amino acid (threonine) by extending the carbon skeleton by one carbon unit. Formaldehyde is a key C1 electrophile that is abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids from reduction of CO2 and Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.\n\nThis pathway links threonine synthesis to L-alanine, which is itself produced by multiple prebiotic routes including: (a) reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine in the presence of iron (Muchowska et al., 2019), (b) hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015), and (c) reduction of L-serine under hydrothermal conditions (Aubrey et al., 2008). The reaction is directly analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation demonstrated by the same research group, but applied one carbon unit higher in the amino acid homologous series.\n\n## 2. Key Intermediates and Precursors\n\n### Hub Molecule: L-Alanine (C3H7NO2)\n- Formula: C3H7NO2\n- SMILES: CC(C(=O)O)N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\n- MW: 89.09\n- Role: **Key amino acid precursor for Pathway 2** \u2014 L-alanine is the substrate for the aldol condensation with formaldehyde that produces threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008). Alanine is itself produced by multiple prebiotic routes: reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine using iron catalysts at 70\u00b0C (Muchowska et al., 2019), hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015), and reduction of L-serine under hydrothermal conditions (Aubrey et al., 2008). Alanine is one of the most abundant amino acids produced in prebiotic chemistry experiments.\n\n### Key Intermediate: Cyanohydrin Intermediate (C5H9NO2)\n- Formula: C5H9NO2\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c1-4(7)2-5(8)3-6/h4-5,7-8H,2H2,1H3\n- MW: 115.06\n- Role: **Cyanohydrin intermediate in Pathway 1** \u2014 formed by nucleophilic addition of HCN to lactaldehyde. This intermediate is the direct precursor to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile via amination with ammonia. Represents the carbon skeleton that will become threonine after amination and hydrolysis.\n\n### Key Intermediate: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O)\n- Formula: C4H8N2O\n- SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\n- MW: 100.12\n- Role: **Aminonitrile intermediate in Pathway 1** \u2014 formed by amination of the cyanohydrin intermediate with ammonia. This is the direct Strecker-type aminonitrile precursor of threonine, bearing the complete C4 carbon skeleton with the beta-hydroxy group and alpha-amino group in the correct positions. Hydrolysis of the nitrile group yields threonine.\n\n### Other Key Molecules\n\n**Lactaldehyde** (C3H6O2)\n- Formula: C3H6O2\n- SMILES: CC(C=O)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\n- MW: 74.08\n- Role: Starting aldehyde for Pathway 1 \u2014 undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN to initiate the cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis. Lactaldehyde is a C3 hydroxy aldehyde that is prebiotically plausible as a product of aldol chemistry and sugar photochemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions.\n\n**Hydrogen Cyanide** (CHN)\n- Formula: CHN\n- SMILES: C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- MW: 27.03\n- Role: Key C1 nucleophile for cyanohydrin formation in Pathway 1. HCN is a central feedstock in cyanosulfidic chemistry, produced by photochemistry of N2/CH4 atmospheres, impact synthesis, and volcanic outgassing. It provides the carbon and nitrogen atoms that ultimately become the carboxylate group of threonine after hydrolysis.\n\n**Formaldehyde** (CH2O)\n- Formula: CH2O\n- SMILES: C=O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\n- MW: 30.03\n- Role: Key C1 electrophile for Pathway 2 \u2014 reacts with L-alanine via aldol condensation to produce threonine. Formaldehyde is a common prebiotic starting molecule produced by photoreduction of CO2, hydrothermal reduction of CO2, Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on mineral surfaces, and UV photolysis of methane.\n\n### Starting Molecules\n- **H2O**: SMILES: O, InChI: InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\n- **NH3** (ammonia): SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\n- **HCN** (hydrogen cyanide): SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- **H2CO** (formaldehyde): SMILES: C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\n\n## 3. Reaction Mechanisms and Conditions\n\n### Reactions Producing Intermediates (Upstream)\n\n**Reaction U1: HCN cyanohydrin addition to lactaldehyde**\n- Lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 Cyanohydrin intermediate\n- SMILES: CC(O)C=O.C#N>>CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of lactaldehyde, forming a cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani reaction that extends the carbon chain by one unit. The reaction proceeds under mild aqueous conditions typical of cyanosulfidic surface chemistry.\n\n**Reaction U2: Aminonitrile formation from cyanohydrin + ammonia**\n- Cyanohydrin intermediate + NH3 \u2192 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + H2O\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N.N>>CC(O)C(N)C#N.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement of the carbon skeleton to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.\n\n### Reactions Producing L-Threonine (Final Steps)\n\n**Reaction F1: Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile**\n- 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Threonine + NH3\n- SMILES: CC(O)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(O)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide), which further hydrolyzes to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia. This is the terminal step of the general Strecker/cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid conversion.\n\n**Reaction F2: Aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde**\n- L-Alanine + Formaldehyde \u2192 L-Threonine\n- SMILES: C[C@H](N)C(=O)O.C=O>>C[C@@H](O)[C@H](N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Hydrothermal (submarine hydrothermal systems)\n- Conditions: Elevated temperature and pressure\n- Source: Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008), *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, DOI: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2\n- Mechanism: Aldol condensation \u2014 the alpha-carbon of L-alanine attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a beta-hydroxyl group. This extends the C3 amino acid (alanine) to the C4 amino acid (threonine). The reaction is analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation from the same study.\n\n## 4. Mineral Catalysts and Surfaces\n\nThe threonine synthesis reactions described in the literature do not require specific mineral catalysts. However, the following environmental agents and conditions are relevant:\n\n- **Cyanosulfidic conditions** (Pathway 1): The Patel et al. (2015) reactions operate under the cyanosulfidic chemistry framework, which involves hydrogen cyanide (HCN), hydrogen sulfide (H2S), and UV irradiation in surface pools. While no specific mineral catalysts are documented for the threonine-specific reactions, the broader cyanosulfidic network utilizes phosphate minerals for phosphorylation and UV light as an energy source.\n\n- **Hydrothermal mineral surfaces** (Pathway 2): The Aubrey et al. (2008) aldol condensation operates under submarine hydrothermal conditions. While no specific mineral catalyst is documented for the alanine-formaldehyde condensation itself, the hydrothermal environment provides elevated temperatures and mineral surfaces (e.g., iron-sulfide minerals, clay minerals) that may facilitate the reaction. Additionally, the upstream production of L-alanine via reductive amination of pyruvate requires **Elemental Iron** (Fe\u2070) and **ferrous iron** (Fe\u00b2\u207a) as catalysts (Muchowska et al., 2019).\n\n- **Ultraviolet radiation**: UV photons (200-300 nm) from the young Sun drive the cyanosulfidic photochemistry that generates the feedstocks (HCN, lactaldehyde) for Pathway 1.\n\n## 5. Experimental Evidence\n\n### Study 1: Patel et al. (2015)\n- **Title**: \"Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism\"\n- **Journal**: Nature Chemistry\n- **DOI**: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- **Key finding**: Demonstrated that a unified cyanosulfidic chemistry starting from HCN and H2S can produce precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids. For threonine specifically, the paper describes a three-step pathway: (1) HCN cyanohydrin addition to lactaldehyde produces a cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2), (2) amination with ammonia converts the cyanohydrin to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O), and (3) nitrile hydrolysis yields L-threonine with release of ammonia. This is the cyanosulfidic analog of the Strecker synthesis, where the starting aldehyde (lactaldehyde) determines the amino acid product (threonine). The same framework produces glycine (from formaldehyde), alanine (from acetaldehyde), serine (from glycolaldehyde), and valine (from dihydroxyacetone-derived acetone), demonstrating a unified chemical origin for the amino acid repertoire.\n\n### Study 2: Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008)\n- **Title**: \"The Role of Submarine Hydrothermal Systems in the Synthesis of Amino Acids\"\n- **Journal**: Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres\n- **DOI**: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2\n- **Key finding**: Investigated amino acid synthesis under simulated submarine hydrothermal vent conditions. Demonstrated that L-alanine reacts with formaldehyde to produce L-threonine via aldol condensation. This reaction extends the carbon skeleton of a simpler amino acid (alanine, C3) to a more complex one (threonine, C4) by incorporating a C1 unit (formaldehyde). The same study demonstrated the analogous glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation, as well as serine reduction to alanine. These reactions establish a hydrothermal amino acid interconversion network where simpler amino acids serve as building blocks for more complex ones through aldol chemistry with formaldehyde.\n\n## 6. Environmental Context\n\n### Surface Environment (Primary for Pathway 1)\nThe cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015) operates under surface conditions:\n- **Cyanosulfidic nitrile chemistry**: Lactaldehyde reacts with HCN to form a cyanohydrin, which is aminated by ammonia and then hydrolyzed to threonine. This operates in surface pools where HCN-derived chemistry (UV-driven, evaporitic) produces aminonitrile intermediates that hydrolyze in wet phases.\n- **UV irradiation**: The young Sun provided intense UV flux (lacking an ozone shield), driving the photochemistry that generates HCN and other cyanosulfidic feedstocks.\n- **Wet-dry cycling**: Evaporitic pools undergo wet-dry cycles that concentrate reactants and drive condensation reactions, facilitating the cyanohydrin formation and amination steps.\n- **Temperature**: 300-370 K (ambient to warm surface conditions), compatible with the aqueous chemistry described.\n\n### Hydrothermal Environment (Primary for Pathway 2)\nThe aldol condensation pathway (Aubrey et al., 2008) operates under submarine hydrothermal conditions:\n- **L-Alanine availability**: L-alanine is produced by iron-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate at 70\u00b0C (Muchowska et al., 2019), by reduction of L-serine (Aubrey et al., 2008), and by cyanosulfidic aminonitrile hydrolysis (Patel et al., 2015). Multiple upstream pathways feed alanine into the hydrothermal environment.\n- **Formaldehyde availability**: Formaldehyde is produced by hydrothermal reduction of CO2 and by Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on native iron and nickel-iron mineral surfaces. It is a key C1 building block abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids.\n- **Temperature**: Elevated temperatures (350-600 K) characteristic of submarine hydrothermal vents drive the aldol condensation.\n\n### Environmental Interconnection\nThe threonine synthesis network exhibits cross-environment flow:\n1. **Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal**: L-Alanine produced by cyanosulfidic chemistry (Pathway 1-type aminonitrile hydrolysis in surface pools) could be transported to hydrothermal environments, where it undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde (Pathway 2).\n2. **Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface**: Alanine and formaldehyde generated at hydrothermal vents could be transported to surface environments via ocean circulation.\n3. **Parallel independent routes**: The two pathways operate independently in different environments (surface cyanosulfidic vs. hydrothermal aldol), providing robustness to the prebiotic threonine synthesis network.\n4. **Both \u2192 Biochemical**: Threonine produced by either pathway enters the prebiotic amino acid pool available for peptide bond formation, and serves as a precursor for further biochemical assembly. Threonine itself can thermally decompose to glycine under hydrothermal conditions (Vallentyne, 1964; Bada et al., 1978), linking it to the broader amino acid recycling network.\n\n## 7. Open Questions and Challenges\n\n1. **Chirality**: Both demonstrated prebiotic routes produce racemic threonine (equal L and D forms). The origin of homochirality (biological preference for L-amino acids) remains unresolved. Mineral surface adsorption, photolysis with circularly polarized light, or amplification through autocatalytic crystallization have been proposed but not demonstrated specifically for threonine.\n\n2. **Lactaldehyde availability**: Pathway 1 requires lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropionaldehyde), whose prebiotic abundance and stability are debated. It could form from aldol chemistry of simpler aldehydes (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde), from sugar photochemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions, or from reduction of pyruvaldehyde. Quantitative constraints on its steady-state concentration in surface environments are needed.\n\n3. **Threonine thermal stability**: Threonine is thermally labile and decomposes to glycine under hydrothermal conditions (Vallentyne, 1964; Bada et al., 1978). The balance between threonine production (via aldol condensation, Pathway 2) and thermal decomposition at hydrothermal temperatures is a key kinetic question. The retro-aldol decomposition of threonine to glycine (the reverse of the serine-type aldol reaction) may limit threonine accumulation in hydrothermal systems.\n\n4. **2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile stability**: Pathway 1 requires this aminonitrile intermediate to persist long enough for hydrolysis. Its stability under UV irradiation, varying pH, and temperature fluctuations in surface pools needs further study. Competing reactions (polymerization, reaction with other HCN-derived species) could reduce yields.\n\n5. **Formaldehyde concentration**: Pathway 2 requires formaldehyde, which is volatile and reactive. Its prebiotic concentration in hydrothermal environments is debated. Mineral adsorption, continuous production from CO2 reduction via serpentinization-derived H2, and thermophoretic concentration may maintain sufficient steady-state levels.\n\n6. **Alanine as precursor**: Pathway 2 requires L-alanine as a substrate, which must itself be produced by upstream prebiotic reactions. The availability of alanine in sufficient concentrations at hydrothermal vents, where it is simultaneously being consumed by aldol condensation and potentially decomposed at high temperatures, represents a kinetic bottleneck that needs quantitative modeling.\n\n7. **Selectivity and side products**: The aldol condensation of alanine with formaldehyde (Pathway 2) could potentially produce other isomeric products besides threonine. The stereoselectivity and regioselectivity of this reaction under prebiotic conditions, and the relative yields of threonine versus allo-threonine or other isomers, need further characterization.\n\n=== END CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Two experimentally demonstrated prebiotic routes converge on L-threonine: (1) a cyanosulfidic surface pathway starting from lactaldehyde and HCN via cyanohydrin and aminonitrile intermediates (Patel et al., 2015), and (2) a hydrothermal aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde (Aubrey et al., 2008). The network traces these pathways back to simple C1 starting materials (CO2, H2, HCN, NH3) through hydrothermal carbon fixation, surface aldol and formose chemistry, and cyanosulfidic nitrile transformations. Key hub molecules\u2014formaldehyde, pyruvate, L-alanine, and ammonia\u2014interconnect the hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments, creating a robust, redundant network with multiple independent routes to threonine.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropionaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactaldehyde cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO2/c1-3(6)2-4(7)5/h3-4,6-7H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-aminopropanenitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2H,4H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is reduced to formate (HCOO\u207b) via hydride transfer on the greigite surface, which acts as a structural analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under the strongly reducing conditions of alkaline hydrothermal vents.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is well established in hydrothermal prebiotic chemistry. Greigite's structural similarity to biological iron-sulfur clusters supports its role as an abiotic CO2 fixation catalyst (Roldan et al., 2015; Herschy et al., 2014). Formate is the first stable C1 intermediate in hydrothermal carbon fixation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde from CO2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), native iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions in submarine hydrothermal systems\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is first reduced to CO on magnetite/native iron surfaces, followed by further hydrogenation to formaldehyde via Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) surface chemistry. The reaction proceeds through adsorbed CO intermediates on the mineral surface that are progressively hydrogenated.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formaldehyde production from CO2 and H2 via Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite and native iron surfaces has been documented in hydrothermal systems. Formaldehyde is identified as a key C1 electrophile abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids (Aubrey et al., 2008; McCollom & Seewald, 2007). This supplies the C1 building block required for both the formose pathway (Pathway 1) and the aldol condensation with alanine (Pathway 2).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite, magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions; multi-step reductive carbon fixation analogous to rTCA cycle\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces produces pyruvate through formate and acetate intermediates, analogous to the reductive tricarboxylic acid (rTCA) cycle. This involves stepwise reduction of CO2 to C1, C2, and C3 units on mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from CO2 and H2 on iron-sulfur and iron-oxide mineral surfaces has been demonstrated as part of a prebiotic analog of the rTCA cycle (Muchowska et al., 2017; Varma et al., 2018). Pyruvate is a central metabolic hub molecule that feeds into amino acid synthesis. Its formation under hydrothermal conditions provides the C3 backbone for alanine and, ultimately, threonine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose reaction: formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)2, borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline evaporitic pool conditions; borate stabilizes sugar intermediates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol self-condensation of two formaldehyde molecules to produce glycolaldehyde (the simplest sugar). The reaction is base-catalyzed: OH\u207b deprotonates formaldehyde hydrate to form a nucleophilic enolate that attacks a second formaldehyde molecule. Borate minerals stabilize the glycolaldehyde product against further uncontrolled condensation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction producing glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is well-established prebiotic chemistry (Breslow, 1959; Ricardo et al., 2004). Borate minerals stabilize sugars and prevent the runaway polymerization that plagues the classical formose reaction (Ricardo et al., 2004). Glycolaldehyde is a key C2 building block for sugar and aldehyde chain extension, and serves as the precursor to lactaldehyde needed for Pathway 1 threonine synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, Ca(OH)2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline evaporitic pool conditions; clay surfaces concentrate and orient reactants\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Base-catalyzed aldol condensation: the alpha-carbon of glycolaldehyde is deprotonated to form an enolate nucleophile, which attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde. The product is lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropionaldehyde), a C3 hydroxy-aldehyde. Montmorillonite clay surfaces adsorb and concentrate the reactants.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Lactaldehyde is a prebiotically plausible C3 aldol product available from aldol chemistry of simpler aldehydes (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde) under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015). This reaction connects the formose chemistry to the cyanosulfidic threonine pathway. Lactaldehyde serves as the critical aldehyde that introduces the methyl branch distinguishing threonine from serine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation from lactaldehyde and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (phosphate buffer)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions in surface evaporitic pools; mildly basic pH buffered by phosphate\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide ion (CN\u207b) to the electrophilic aldehyde carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde. The cyanide ion attacks the carbonyl carbon, and subsequent protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani-type cyanohydrin reaction that extends the carbon chain by one unit while introducing a nitrile functional group.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is the first step of the cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis pathway demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry). HCN-derived cyanohydrin formation is a central transformation in the broader Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry framework. Phosphate minerals buffer pH and may facilitate the reaction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker-type amination of cyanohydrin to aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (UV may assist)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions; UV irradiation may assist the amination; wet-dry cycling concentrates reactants\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Strecker-type amination: ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the second step of the cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis demonstrated by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry). The Strecker-type amination is a well-established transformation in prebiotic aminonitrile chemistry. The reaction parallels the broader cyanosulfidic strategy where ammonia amination of cyanohydrins is a general route to aminonitrile amino acid precursors.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile to L-threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surface, mild acid/base\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools; clay surfaces may catalyze hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis: water first attacks the nitrile carbon of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide). Further hydrolysis of the amide yields the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia. This is the terminal step of the cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid conversion.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the final step of the cyanosulfidic threonine pathway demonstrated by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry). Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid via amide intermediate is well-established chemistry. The released ammonia recycles into the network as a reactant for further amination reactions, creating a catalytic loop. Note that this step produces racemic threonine; the origin of homochirality remains an open question.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to L-alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron (Fe0), Fe2+\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"70\u00b0C, iron-catalyzed reductive amination with hydroxylamine/ammonia as nitrogen source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive amination: ammonia attacks the ketone carbonyl of pyruvate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The imine is then reduced by Fe\u2070 (or Fe\u00b2\u207a/H\u2082) to yield L-alanine. Iron serves as both the reducing agent and Lewis acid catalyst. The reaction converts the alpha-keto acid (pyruvate) to the corresponding alpha-amino acid (alanine).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Iron-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine has been experimentally demonstrated by Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019). The reaction proceeds at 70\u00b0C using elemental iron as reductant and ammonia/hydroxylamine as nitrogen source. This is part of a broader proto-metabolic network where alpha-keto acids are interconverted with amino acids. Alanine is one of the most abundant amino acids in prebiotic chemistry experiments and is the direct precursor for the aldol route to threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde to L-threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surfaces (iron-sulfide, iron-oxide)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Submarine hydrothermal vent conditions; elevated temperature and pressure drive the aldol condensation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol-type condensation: the alpha-carbon of L-alanine is deprotonated and attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a beta-hydroxyl group (-CH(OH)-). This converts the C3 amino acid (alanine) into the C4 amino acid (threonine) by extending the carbon skeleton by one unit. The reaction is directly analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Demonstrated by Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres) under simulated submarine hydrothermal vent conditions. This reaction establishes a hydrothermal amino acid interconversion network where simpler amino acids serve as building blocks for more complex ones through aldol chemistry with formaldehyde. While no specific mineral catalyst was documented for this particular step, the hydrothermal environment provides mineral surfaces (iron-sulfide, iron-oxide) that likely facilitate the reaction. The reaction may produce both threonine and allo-threonine stereoisomers.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (thermal)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Thermal decarboxylation under mild hydrothermal or geothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Non-oxidative decarboxylation of pyruvate: loss of CO2 from the carboxyl group of pyruvate yields acetaldehyde. The reaction is thermally driven and proceeds readily at elevated temperatures. The resulting acetaldehyde retains the C2 unit and the aldehyde functionality needed for Strecker-type chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde is a well-established reaction that occurs readily under prebiotic conditions. This reaction links the hydrothermal pyruvate hub to the surface cyanosulfidic alanine synthesis pathway. Acetaldehyde is identified as the starting aldehyde for alanine production via the Strecker/cyanosulfidic route in the Patel et al. (2015) framework, where acetaldehyde + HCN produces the aminonitrile precursor to alanine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of 2-aminopropanenitrile from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (cyanosulfidic conditions)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions in surface evaporitic pools; sequential cyanohydrin formation and amination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Classic Strecker synthesis: (1) HCN adds to the aldehyde carbonyl of acetaldehyde to form a cyanohydrin intermediate (lactonitrile), (2) ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group to form 2-aminopropanenitrile (alpha-aminonitrile). This two-step sequence converts a C2 aldehyde into a C3 aminonitrile bearing the alanine carbon skeleton.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The cyanosulfidic production of alanine from acetaldehyde via aminonitrile is part of the unified protometabolism described by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry). The same framework that produces threonine from lactaldehyde also produces alanine from acetaldehyde, demonstrating how a single chemical logic (aldehyde + HCN \u2192 cyanohydrin \u2192 aminonitrile \u2192 amino acid) generates the amino acid repertoire. This provides a surface-environment alternative route to alanine that complements the hydrothermal reductive amination (rxn_009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile to L-alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous hydrolysis in surface pools; wet-dry cycling may concentrate aminonitrile before hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis: water attacks the nitrile carbon of 2-aminopropanenitrile, forming 2-aminopropanamide as an intermediate. Further hydrolysis yields alanine with release of ammonia. This is the same nitrile-to-carboxylic-acid conversion as in rxn_008 but applied to the C3 aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the terminal step of the cyanosulfidic amino acid synthesis described by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry). This reaction provides a second, independent route to L-alanine (complementing the hydrothermal reductive amination in rxn_009), establishing alanine as a convergence point in the network. The released ammonia is recycled for further amination reactions.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full cyanosulfidic surface pathway to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete surface-environment route from CO2/H2 through formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, lactaldehyde, and cyanosulfidic nitrile chemistry to threonine. Formaldehyde is produced hydrothermally and transported to surface pools where formose and cyanosulfidic chemistry operate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal aldol pathway via reductive amination of pyruvate\",\n      \"description\": \"Purely hydrothermal route: CO2 fixation produces pyruvate and formaldehyde; pyruvate undergoes iron-catalyzed reductive amination to alanine; alanine condenses with formaldehyde via aldol reaction to produce threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cross-environment pathway: hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 surface cyanosulfidic alanine \u2192 hydrothermal aldol threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate produced hydrothermally is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, which enters surface cyanosulfidic chemistry to produce alanine via Strecker synthesis. Alanine is then transported back to hydrothermal setting for aldol condensation with formaldehyde to produce threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic alanine to hydrothermal aldol threonine (short cross-environment)\",\n      \"description\": \"L-alanine produced by surface cyanosulfidic Strecker synthesis (from acetaldehyde + HCN + NH3) is transported to hydrothermal environment for aldol condensation with formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C1 fixation to surface cyanosulfidic threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction produces formate and formaldehyde as C1 building blocks. Formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where formose chemistry and cyanosulfidic nitrile pathways construct threonine via lactaldehyde.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate hub to alanine via hydrothermal reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Focused pathway from the pyruvate hub molecule through iron-catalyzed reductive amination to alanine, then aldol condensation with formaldehyde to threonine. Highlights the role of pyruvate as a central metabolic hub.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminonitrile core pathway (cyanosulfidic threonine-specific)\",\n      \"description\": \"The core three-step cyanosulfidic pathway from lactaldehyde to threonine: cyanohydrin formation, amination, and nitrile hydrolysis. This is the experimentally demonstrated Patel et al. (2015) pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate decarboxylation to cyanosulfidic alanine pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is thermally decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, which undergoes Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH3 in surface pools to produce the aminonitrile precursor of alanine. Hydrolysis yields alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual C1 fixation to formose-cyanosulfidic threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Two parallel CO2 fixation reactions produce formaldehyde (Fischer-Tropsch) and formate (greigite). Formaldehyde drives formose chemistry to glycolaldehyde and then lactaldehyde, which enters the cyanosulfidic pathway. Demonstrates redundancy in C1 fixation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent dual-environment threonine via ammonia recycling\",\n      \"description\": \"Ammonia released during nitrile hydrolysis (rxn_008 or rxn_013) is recycled into reductive amination (rxn_009) or amination (rxn_007) reactions, creating a catalytic ammonia cycle. This pathway emphasizes NH3 as a hub molecule connecting cyanosulfidic and hydrothermal environments in threonine production.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde is the central C1 building block. Produced hydrothermally by Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, it feeds into three distinct downstream reactions: formose self-condensation to glycolaldehyde, aldol condensation with glycolaldehyde to lactaldehyde, and aldol condensation with alanine to threonine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"description\": \"L-Alanine is produced by two independent pathways: hydrothermal iron-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate (Muchowska et al., 2019) and surface cyanosulfidic Strecker synthesis from acetaldehyde (Patel et al., 2015). Both routes converge on alanine, which then undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to produce threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is the central alpha-keto acid metabolic hub. Produced by hydrothermal CO2 fixation, it branches into two pathways: direct reductive amination to alanine (hydrothermal) and decarboxylation to acetaldehyde (which feeds the surface cyanosulfidic alanine route). This creates a metabolic branch point connecting hydrothermal and surface environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"description\": \"Ammonia is a key nitrogen carrier that participates in both Strecker-type amination reactions (surface) and reductive amination (hydrothermal). It is regenerated by nitrile hydrolysis reactions, creating a catalytic nitrogen cycle that links the cyanosulfidic and hydrothermal environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [],\n      \"description\": \"L-Threonine is the terminal convergence point produced by two independent pathways: surface cyanosulfidic nitrile hydrolysis (Patel et al., 2015) and hydrothermal aldol condensation of alanine with formaldehyde (Aubrey et al., 2008). The dual routes operating in different environments provide robustness to the prebiotic threonine synthesis network.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Threonine", "overall_strategy": "Two experimentally demonstrated prebiotic routes converge on L-threonine: (1) a cyanosulfidic surface pathway starting from lactaldehyde and HCN via cyanohydrin and aminonitrile intermediates (Patel et al., 2015), and (2) a hydrothermal aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde (Aubrey et al., 2008). The network traces these pathways back to simple C1 starting materials (CO2, H2, HCN, NH3) through hydrothermal carbon fixation, surface aldol and formose chemistry, and cyanosulfidic nitrile transformations. Key hub molecules\u2014formaldehyde, pyruvate, L-alanine, and ammonia\u2014interconnect the hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments, creating a robust, redundant network with multiple independent routes to threonine.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H3N", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "formic acid", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "glycolaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropionaldehyde", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "L-alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "lactaldehyde cyanohydrin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO2/c1-3(6)2-4(7)5/h3-4,6-7H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "L-threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C3H4N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "2-aminopropanenitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2H,4H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is reduced to formate (HCOO\u207b) via hydride transfer on the greigite surface, which acts as a structural analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under the strongly reducing conditions of alkaline hydrothermal vents.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is well established in hydrothermal prebiotic chemistry. Greigite's structural similarity to biological iron-sulfur clusters supports its role as an abiotic CO2 fixation catalyst (Roldan et al., 2015; Herschy et al., 2014). Formate is the first stable C1 intermediate in hydrothermal carbon fixation."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde from CO2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), native iron", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions in submarine hydrothermal systems"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is first reduced to CO on magnetite/native iron surfaces, followed by further hydrogenation to formaldehyde via Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) surface chemistry. The reaction proceeds through adsorbed CO intermediates on the mineral surface that are progressively hydrogenated.", "reasoning": "Formaldehyde production from CO2 and H2 via Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite and native iron surfaces has been documented in hydrothermal systems. Formaldehyde is identified as a key C1 electrophile abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids (Aubrey et al., 2008; McCollom & Seewald, 2007). This supplies the C1 building block required for both the formose pathway (Pathway 1) and the aldol condensation with alanine (Pathway 2)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite, magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions; multi-step reductive carbon fixation analogous to rTCA cycle"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces produces pyruvate through formate and acetate intermediates, analogous to the reductive tricarboxylic acid (rTCA) cycle. This involves stepwise reduction of CO2 to C1, C2, and C3 units on mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate from CO2 and H2 on iron-sulfur and iron-oxide mineral surfaces has been demonstrated as part of a prebiotic analog of the rTCA cycle (Muchowska et al., 2017; Varma et al., 2018). Pyruvate is a central metabolic hub molecule that feeds into amino acid synthesis. Its formation under hydrothermal conditions provides the C3 backbone for alanine and, ultimately, threonine."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Formose reaction: formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)2, borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline evaporitic pool conditions; borate stabilizes sugar intermediates"}, "mechanism": "Aldol self-condensation of two formaldehyde molecules to produce glycolaldehyde (the simplest sugar). The reaction is base-catalyzed: OH\u207b deprotonates formaldehyde hydrate to form a nucleophilic enolate that attacks a second formaldehyde molecule. Borate minerals stabilize the glycolaldehyde product against further uncontrolled condensation.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction producing glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is well-established prebiotic chemistry (Breslow, 1959; Ricardo et al., 2004). Borate minerals stabilize sugars and prevent the runaway polymerization that plagues the classical formose reaction (Ricardo et al., 2004). Glycolaldehyde is a key C2 building block for sugar and aldehyde chain extension, and serves as the precursor to lactaldehyde needed for Pathway 1 threonine synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, Ca(OH)2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline evaporitic pool conditions; clay surfaces concentrate and orient reactants"}, "mechanism": "Base-catalyzed aldol condensation: the alpha-carbon of glycolaldehyde is deprotonated to form an enolate nucleophile, which attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde. The product is lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropionaldehyde), a C3 hydroxy-aldehyde. Montmorillonite clay surfaces adsorb and concentrate the reactants.", "reasoning": "Lactaldehyde is a prebiotically plausible C3 aldol product available from aldol chemistry of simpler aldehydes (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde) under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015). This reaction connects the formose chemistry to the cyanosulfidic threonine pathway. Lactaldehyde serves as the critical aldehyde that introduces the methyl branch distinguishing threonine from serine."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation from lactaldehyde and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (phosphate buffer)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions in surface evaporitic pools; mildly basic pH buffered by phosphate"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide ion (CN\u207b) to the electrophilic aldehyde carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde. The cyanide ion attacks the carbonyl carbon, and subsequent protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani-type cyanohydrin reaction that extends the carbon chain by one unit while introducing a nitrile functional group.", "reasoning": "This reaction is the first step of the cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis pathway demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry). HCN-derived cyanohydrin formation is a central transformation in the broader Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry framework. Phosphate minerals buffer pH and may facilitate the reaction."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Strecker-type amination of cyanohydrin to aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (UV may assist)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions; UV irradiation may assist the amination; wet-dry cycling concentrates reactants"}, "mechanism": "Strecker-type amination: ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.", "reasoning": "This is the second step of the cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis demonstrated by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry). The Strecker-type amination is a well-established transformation in prebiotic aminonitrile chemistry. The reaction parallels the broader cyanosulfidic strategy where ammonia amination of cyanohydrins is a general route to aminonitrile amino acid precursors."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile to L-threonine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surface, mild acid/base", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools; clay surfaces may catalyze hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis: water first attacks the nitrile carbon of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide). Further hydrolysis of the amide yields the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia. This is the terminal step of the cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid conversion.", "reasoning": "This is the final step of the cyanosulfidic threonine pathway demonstrated by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry). Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acid via amide intermediate is well-established chemistry. The released ammonia recycles into the network as a reactant for further amination reactions, creating a catalytic loop. Note that this step produces racemic threonine; the origin of homochirality remains an open question."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to L-alanine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-350K", "pressure": "1 atm to moderate", "catalyst": "elemental iron (Fe0), Fe2+", "aqueous": "true", "other": "70\u00b0C, iron-catalyzed reductive amination with hydroxylamine/ammonia as nitrogen source"}, "mechanism": "Reductive amination: ammonia attacks the ketone carbonyl of pyruvate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The imine is then reduced by Fe\u2070 (or Fe\u00b2\u207a/H\u2082) to yield L-alanine. Iron serves as both the reducing agent and Lewis acid catalyst. The reaction converts the alpha-keto acid (pyruvate) to the corresponding alpha-amino acid (alanine).", "reasoning": "Iron-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine has been experimentally demonstrated by Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019). The reaction proceeds at 70\u00b0C using elemental iron as reductant and ammonia/hydroxylamine as nitrogen source. This is part of a broader proto-metabolic network where alpha-keto acids are interconverted with amino acids. Alanine is one of the most abundant amino acids in prebiotic chemistry experiments and is the direct precursor for the aldol route to threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde to L-threonine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mineral surfaces (iron-sulfide, iron-oxide)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Submarine hydrothermal vent conditions; elevated temperature and pressure drive the aldol condensation"}, "mechanism": "Aldol-type condensation: the alpha-carbon of L-alanine is deprotonated and attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a beta-hydroxyl group (-CH(OH)-). This converts the C3 amino acid (alanine) into the C4 amino acid (threonine) by extending the carbon skeleton by one unit. The reaction is directly analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation.", "reasoning": "Demonstrated by Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres) under simulated submarine hydrothermal vent conditions. This reaction establishes a hydrothermal amino acid interconversion network where simpler amino acids serve as building blocks for more complex ones through aldol chemistry with formaldehyde. While no specific mineral catalyst was documented for this particular step, the hydrothermal environment provides mineral surfaces (iron-sulfide, iron-oxide) that likely facilitate the reaction. The reaction may produce both threonine and allo-threonine stereoisomers."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_001"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "1 atm to moderate", "catalyst": "none (thermal)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Thermal decarboxylation under mild hydrothermal or geothermal conditions"}, "mechanism": "Non-oxidative decarboxylation of pyruvate: loss of CO2 from the carboxyl group of pyruvate yields acetaldehyde. The reaction is thermally driven and proceeds readily at elevated temperatures. The resulting acetaldehyde retains the C2 unit and the aldehyde functionality needed for Strecker-type chemistry.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde is a well-established reaction that occurs readily under prebiotic conditions. This reaction links the hydrothermal pyruvate hub to the surface cyanosulfidic alanine synthesis pathway. Acetaldehyde is identified as the starting aldehyde for alanine production via the Strecker/cyanosulfidic route in the Patel et al. (2015) framework, where acetaldehyde + HCN produces the aminonitrile precursor to alanine."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Strecker synthesis of 2-aminopropanenitrile from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_005", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (cyanosulfidic conditions)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions in surface evaporitic pools; sequential cyanohydrin formation and amination"}, "mechanism": "Classic Strecker synthesis: (1) HCN adds to the aldehyde carbonyl of acetaldehyde to form a cyanohydrin intermediate (lactonitrile), (2) ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group to form 2-aminopropanenitrile (alpha-aminonitrile). This two-step sequence converts a C2 aldehyde into a C3 aminonitrile bearing the alanine carbon skeleton.", "reasoning": "The cyanosulfidic production of alanine from acetaldehyde via aminonitrile is part of the unified protometabolism described by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry). The same framework that produces threonine from lactaldehyde also produces alanine from acetaldehyde, demonstrating how a single chemical logic (aldehyde + HCN \u2192 cyanohydrin \u2192 aminonitrile \u2192 amino acid) generates the amino acid repertoire. This provides a surface-environment alternative route to alanine that complements the hydrothermal reductive amination (rxn_009)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile to L-alanine", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Aqueous hydrolysis in surface pools; wet-dry cycling may concentrate aminonitrile before hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis: water attacks the nitrile carbon of 2-aminopropanenitrile, forming 2-aminopropanamide as an intermediate. Further hydrolysis yields alanine with release of ammonia. This is the same nitrile-to-carboxylic-acid conversion as in rxn_008 but applied to the C3 aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the terminal step of the cyanosulfidic amino acid synthesis described by Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry). This reaction provides a second, independent route to L-alanine (complementing the hydrothermal reductive amination in rxn_009), establishing alanine as a convergence point in the network. The released ammonia is recycled for further amination reactions."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full cyanosulfidic surface pathway to threonine", "description": "Complete surface-environment route from CO2/H2 through formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, lactaldehyde, and cyanosulfidic nitrile chemistry to threonine. Formaldehyde is produced hydrothermally and transported to surface pools where formose and cyanosulfidic chemistry operate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal aldol pathway via reductive amination of pyruvate", "description": "Purely hydrothermal route: CO2 fixation produces pyruvate and formaldehyde; pyruvate undergoes iron-catalyzed reductive amination to alanine; alanine condenses with formaldehyde via aldol reaction to produce threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_009", "rxn_002", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_006"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Cross-environment pathway: hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 surface cyanosulfidic alanine \u2192 hydrothermal aldol threonine", "description": "Pyruvate produced hydrothermally is decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, which enters surface cyanosulfidic chemistry to produce alanine via Strecker synthesis. Alanine is then transported back to hydrothermal setting for aldol condensation with formaldehyde to produce threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_002", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_015", "mol_016", "mol_011", "mol_006"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Cyanosulfidic alanine to hydrothermal aldol threonine (short cross-environment)", "description": "L-alanine produced by surface cyanosulfidic Strecker synthesis (from acetaldehyde + HCN + NH3) is transported to hydrothermal environment for aldol condensation with formaldehyde.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_016", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hydrothermal C1 fixation to surface cyanosulfidic threonine", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction produces formate and formaldehyde as C1 building blocks. Formaldehyde is transported to surface pools where formose chemistry and cyanosulfidic nitrile pathways construct threonine via lactaldehyde.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Pyruvate hub to alanine via hydrothermal reductive amination", "description": "Focused pathway from the pyruvate hub molecule through iron-catalyzed reductive amination to alanine, then aldol condensation with formaldehyde to threonine. Highlights the role of pyruvate as a central metabolic hub.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Aminonitrile core pathway (cyanosulfidic threonine-specific)", "description": "The core three-step cyanosulfidic pathway from lactaldehyde to threonine: cyanohydrin formation, amination, and nitrile hydrolysis. This is the experimentally demonstrated Patel et al. (2015) pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Pyruvate decarboxylation to cyanosulfidic alanine pathway", "description": "Pyruvate is thermally decarboxylated to acetaldehyde, which undergoes Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH3 in surface pools to produce the aminonitrile precursor of alanine. Hydrolysis yields alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_015", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Dual C1 fixation to formose-cyanosulfidic threonine", "description": "Two parallel CO2 fixation reactions produce formaldehyde (Fischer-Tropsch) and formate (greigite). Formaldehyde drives formose chemistry to glycolaldehyde and then lactaldehyde, which enters the cyanosulfidic pathway. Demonstrates redundancy in C1 fixation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Convergent dual-environment threonine via ammonia recycling", "description": "Ammonia released during nitrile hydrolysis (rxn_008 or rxn_013) is recycled into reductive amination (rxn_009) or amination (rxn_007) reactions, creating a catalytic ammonia cycle. This pathway emphasizes NH3 as a hub molecule connecting cyanosulfidic and hydrothermal environments in threonine production.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_011", "mol_014"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_010", "mol_011"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_006", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_010"], "description": "Formaldehyde is the central C1 building block. Produced hydrothermally by Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, it feeds into three distinct downstream reactions: formose self-condensation to glycolaldehyde, aldol condensation with glycolaldehyde to lactaldehyde, and aldol condensation with alanine to threonine."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010"], "description": "L-Alanine is produced by two independent pathways: hydrothermal iron-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate (Muchowska et al., 2019) and surface cyanosulfidic Strecker synthesis from acetaldehyde (Patel et al., 2015). Both routes converge on alanine, which then undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to produce threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008)."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_011"], "description": "Pyruvate is the central alpha-keto acid metabolic hub. Produced by hydrothermal CO2 fixation, it branches into two pathways: direct reductive amination to alanine (hydrothermal) and decarboxylation to acetaldehyde (which feeds the surface cyanosulfidic alanine route). This creates a metabolic branch point connecting hydrothermal and surface environments."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_004", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_012"], "description": "Ammonia is a key nitrogen carrier that participates in both Strecker-type amination reactions (surface) and reductive amination (hydrothermal). It is regenerated by nitrile hydrolysis reactions, creating a catalytic nitrogen cycle that links the cyanosulfidic and hydrothermal environments."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_010"], "outgoing_reactions": [], "description": "L-Threonine is the terminal convergence point produced by two independent pathways: surface cyanosulfidic nitrile hydrolysis (Patel et al., 2015) and hydrothermal aldol condensation of alanine with formaldehyde (Aubrey et al., 2008). The dual routes operating in different environments provide robustness to the prebiotic threonine synthesis network."}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 400737.3321056366, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T23:40:42.680650", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: L-Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: Two experimentally demonstrated prebiotic routes converge on L-threonine: (1) a cyanosulfidic surface pathway starting from lactaldehyde and HCN via cyanohydrin and aminonitrile intermediates (Patel et al., 2015), and (2) a hydrothermal aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde (Aubrey et al., 2008). The network traces these pathways back to simple C1 starting materials (CO2, H2, HCN, NH3) through hydrothermal carbon fixation, surface aldol and formose chemistry, and cyanosulfidic nitrile transformations. Key hub molecules\u2014formaldehyde, pyruvate, L-alanine, and ammonia\u2014interconnect the hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments, creating a robust, redundant network with multiple independent routes to threonine.\n\nMOLECULES (16 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_004: H3N (ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: CHN (HCN) [starting]\n  - mol_006: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: CH2O2 (formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C3H6O2 (lactaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C3H4O3 (pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C3H7NO2 (L-alanine) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C4H7NO2 (lactaldehyde cyanohydrin) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C4H8N2O (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H9NO3 (L-threonine) [target]\n  - mol_015: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C3H4N2 (2-aminopropanenitrile) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (13 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_006, mol_003 (Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde from CO2) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_010, mol_003 (Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_006, mol_006 -> mol_008 (Formose reaction: formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_008, mol_006 -> mol_009 (Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_009, mol_005 -> mol_012 (Cyanohydrin formation from lactaldehyde and HCN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_012, mol_004 -> mol_013, mol_003 (Strecker-type amination of cyanohydrin to aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_013, mol_003 -> mol_014, mol_004 (Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile to L-threonine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_010, mol_004 -> mol_011, mol_003 (Reductive amination of pyruvate to L-alanine) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_010: mol_011, mol_006 -> mol_014 (Aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde to L-threonine) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_011: mol_010 -> mol_015, mol_001 (Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_012: mol_015, mol_005, mol_004 -> mol_016, mol_003 (Strecker synthesis of 2-aminopropanenitrile from acetaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_016, mol_003 -> mol_011, mol_004 (Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile to L-alanine) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Full cyanosulfidic surface pathway to threonine (6 steps)\n  - P2: Hydrothermal aldol pathway via reductive amination of pyruvate (4 steps)\n  - P3: Cross-environment pathway: hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 surface cyanosulfidic alanine \u2192 hydrothermal aldol threonine (6 steps)\n  - P4: Cyanosulfidic alanine to hydrothermal aldol threonine (short cross-environment) (3 steps)\n  - P5: Hydrothermal C1 fixation to surface cyanosulfidic threonine (7 steps)\n  - P6: Pyruvate hub to alanine via hydrothermal reductive amination (3 steps)\n  - P7: Aminonitrile core pathway (cyanosulfidic threonine-specific) (3 steps)\n  - P8: Pyruvate decarboxylation to cyanosulfidic alanine pathway (4 steps)\n  - P9: Dual C1 fixation to formose-cyanosulfidic threonine (6 steps)\n  - P10: Convergent dual-environment threonine via ammonia recycling (3 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_004, mol_006, mol_010, mol_011\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n# Prebiotic Synthesis of L-Threonine: Comprehensive Literature Review\n\n## 1. Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\n\nTwo experimentally demonstrated pathways produce L-threonine (C4H9NO3, SMILES: CC(C(C(=O)O)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8), MW: 119.12) from prebiotically available precursors. These span surface and hydrothermal environments.\n\n### Pathway 1: Cyanosulfidic Nitrile Hydrolysis via Lactaldehyde Cyanohydrin (Surface Environment)\n\nThe cyanosulfidic protometabolism pathway demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) constructs L-threonine through a 3-step sequence starting from **lactaldehyde** and **hydrogen cyanide**, proceeding through a cyanohydrin intermediate and an aminonitrile intermediate. This pathway follows the general cyanosulfidic strategy: an aldehyde undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN, amination with ammonia displaces the hydroxyl to form an aminonitrile, and final nitrile hydrolysis yields the amino acid.\n\n**Step 1**: Lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 Cyanohydrin intermediate (Cyanohydrin formation)\n- SMILES: CC(O)C=O.C#N>>CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- Reactants: Lactaldehyde (C3H6O2, SMILES: CC(C=O)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3, MW: 74.08) + Hydrogen cyanide (CHN, SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H, MW: 27.03)\n- Product: Cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2, SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c1-4(7)2-5(8)3-6/h4-5,7-8H,2H2,1H3, MW: 115.06)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the aldehyde carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde. The cyanide ion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of the aldehyde, and subsequent protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani-type cyanohydrin reaction that extends the carbon chain by one carbon unit while introducing a nitrile functional group. Lactaldehyde is a plausible prebiotic C3 aldol product available from cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n\n**Step 2**: Cyanohydrin intermediate + NH3 \u2192 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + H2O (Aminonitrile formation)\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N.N>>CC(O)C(N)C#N.O\n- Reactants: Cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2, SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N) + Ammonia (H3N, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3, MW: 17.03)\n- Products: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3, MW: 100.12) + H2O (SMILES: O)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement of the carbon skeleton to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.\n\n**Step 3**: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Threonine + NH3 (Nitrile hydrolysis)\n- SMILES: CC(O)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(O)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Reactants: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O) + 2 H2O (SMILES: O)\n- Products: L-Threonine (C4H9NO3, SMILES: CC(C(C(=O)O)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8), MW: 119.12) + Ammonia (H3N, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of water to the nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide), followed by further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia (NH3). This is the final step of the general cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid pathway, converting the C\u2261N triple bond to a carboxylic acid via stepwise hydration.\n\nThis three-step sequence is part of the broader Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry framework, in which HCN-derived nitriles serve as amino acid precursors via hydrolysis under wet-dry cycling or UV-irradiated surface pool conditions. The same paper demonstrates that this unified chemistry produces precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids from simple feedstocks. The threonine pathway parallels the serine pathway (glycolaldehyde + HCN) but uses lactaldehyde as the starting aldehyde, introducing the methyl branch that distinguishes threonine from serine.\n\n### Pathway 2: Aldol Condensation of L-Alanine with Formaldehyde (Hydrothermal Environment)\n\nAubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, DOI: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2) demonstrated that **L-alanine** (C3H7NO2, SMILES: CC(C(=O)O)N, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6), MW: 89.09) reacts with **formaldehyde** (CH2O, SMILES: C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2, MW: 30.03) to produce L-threonine under submarine hydrothermal conditions.\n\n**Reaction**: L-Alanine + Formaldehyde \u2192 L-Threonine\n- SMILES: C[C@H](N)C(=O)O.C=O>>C[C@@H](O)[C@H](N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Hydrothermal (submarine hydrothermal systems)\n- Conditions: Elevated temperature and pressure characteristic of submarine hydrothermal vents\n- Mechanism: Aldol-type condensation \u2014 the alpha-carbon of L-alanine attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a hydroxymethyl group (-CH(OH)-). This converts the C3 amino acid (alanine) into the C4 amino acid (threonine) by extending the carbon skeleton by one carbon unit. Formaldehyde is a key C1 electrophile that is abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids from reduction of CO2 and Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.\n\nThis pathway links threonine synthesis to L-alanine, which is itself produced by multiple prebiotic routes including: (a) reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine in the presence of iron (Muchowska et al., 2019), (b) hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015), and (c) reduction of L-serine under hydrothermal conditions (Aubrey et al., 2008). The reaction is directly analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation demonstrated by the same research group, but applied one carbon unit higher in the amino acid homologous series.\n\n## 2. Key Intermediates and Precursors\n\n### Hub Molecule: L-Alanine (C3H7NO2)\n- Formula: C3H7NO2\n- SMILES: CC(C(=O)O)N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\n- MW: 89.09\n- Role: **Key amino acid precursor for Pathway 2** \u2014 L-alanine is the substrate for the aldol condensation with formaldehyde that produces threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008). Alanine is itself produced by multiple prebiotic routes: reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine using iron catalysts at 70\u00b0C (Muchowska et al., 2019), hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015), and reduction of L-serine under hydrothermal conditions (Aubrey et al., 2008). Alanine is one of the most abundant amino acids produced in prebiotic chemistry experiments.\n\n### Key Intermediate: Cyanohydrin Intermediate (C5H9NO2)\n- Formula: C5H9NO2\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c1-4(7)2-5(8)3-6/h4-5,7-8H,2H2,1H3\n- MW: 115.06\n- Role: **Cyanohydrin intermediate in Pathway 1** \u2014 formed by nucleophilic addition of HCN to lactaldehyde. This intermediate is the direct precursor to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile via amination with ammonia. Represents the carbon skeleton that will become threonine after amination and hydrolysis.\n\n### Key Intermediate: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O)\n- Formula: C4H8N2O\n- SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\n- MW: 100.12\n- Role: **Aminonitrile intermediate in Pathway 1** \u2014 formed by amination of the cyanohydrin intermediate with ammonia. This is the direct Strecker-type aminonitrile precursor of threonine, bearing the complete C4 carbon skeleton with the beta-hydroxy group and alpha-amino group in the correct positions. Hydrolysis of the nitrile group yields threonine.\n\n### Other Key Molecules\n\n**Lactaldehyde** (C3H6O2)\n- Formula: C3H6O2\n- SMILES: CC(C=O)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\n- MW: 74.08\n- Role: Starting aldehyde for Pathway 1 \u2014 undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN to initiate the cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis. Lactaldehyde is a C3 hydroxy aldehyde that is prebiotically plausible as a product of aldol chemistry and sugar photochemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions.\n\n**Hydrogen Cyanide** (CHN)\n- Formula: CHN\n- SMILES: C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- MW: 27.03\n- Role: Key C1 nucleophile for cyanohydrin formation in Pathway 1. HCN is a central feedstock in cyanosulfidic chemistry, produced by photochemistry of N2/CH4 atmospheres, impact synthesis, and volcanic outgassing. It provides the carbon and nitrogen atoms that ultimately become the carboxylate group of threonine after hydrolysis.\n\n**Formaldehyde** (CH2O)\n- Formula: CH2O\n- SMILES: C=O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\n- MW: 30.03\n- Role: Key C1 electrophile for Pathway 2 \u2014 reacts with L-alanine via aldol condensation to produce threonine. Formaldehyde is a common prebiotic starting molecule produced by photoreduction of CO2, hydrothermal reduction of CO2, Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on mineral surfaces, and UV photolysis of methane.\n\n### Starting Molecules\n- **H2O**: SMILES: O, InChI: InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\n- **NH3** (ammonia): SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\n- **HCN** (hydrogen cyanide): SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- **H2CO** (formaldehyde): SMILES: C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\n\n## 3. Reaction Mechanisms and Conditions\n\n### Reactions Producing Intermediates (Upstream)\n\n**Reaction U1: HCN cyanohydrin addition to lactaldehyde**\n- Lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 Cyanohydrin intermediate\n- SMILES: CC(O)C=O.C#N>>CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of lactaldehyde, forming a cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani reaction that extends the carbon chain by one unit. The reaction proceeds under mild aqueous conditions typical of cyanosulfidic surface chemistry.\n\n**Reaction U2: Aminonitrile formation from cyanohydrin + ammonia**\n- Cyanohydrin intermediate + NH3 \u2192 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + H2O\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N.N>>CC(O)C(N)C#N.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement of the carbon skeleton to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.\n\n### Reactions Producing L-Threonine (Final Steps)\n\n**Reaction F1: Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile**\n- 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Threonine + NH3\n- SMILES: CC(O)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(O)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide), which further hydrolyzes to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia. This is the terminal step of the general Strecker/cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid conversion.\n\n**Reaction F2: Aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde**\n- L-Alanine + Formaldehyde \u2192 L-Threonine\n- SMILES: C[C@H](N)C(=O)O.C=O>>C[C@@H](O)[C@H](N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Hydrothermal (submarine hydrothermal systems)\n- Conditions: Elevated temperature and pressure\n- Source: Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008), *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, DOI: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2\n- Mechanism: Aldol condensation \u2014 the alpha-carbon of L-alanine attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a beta-hydroxyl group. This extends the C3 amino acid (alanine) to the C4 amino acid (threonine). The reaction is analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation from the same study.\n\n## 4. Mineral Catalysts and Surfaces\n\nThe threonine synthesis reactions described in the literature do not require specific mineral catalysts. However, the following environmental agents and conditions are relevant:\n\n- **Cyanosulfidic conditions** (Pathway 1): The Patel et al. (2015) reactions operate under the cyanosulfidic chemistry framework, which involves hydrogen cyanide (HCN), hydrogen sulfide (H2S), and UV irradiation in surface pools. While no specific mineral catalysts are documented for the threonine-specific reactions, the broader cyanosulfidic network utilizes phosphate minerals for phosphorylation and UV light as an energy source.\n\n- **Hydrothermal mineral surfaces** (Pathway 2): The Aubrey et al. (2008) aldol condensation operates under submarine hydrothermal conditions. While no specific mineral catalyst is documented for the alanine-formaldehyde condensation itself, the hydrothermal environment provides elevated temperatures and mineral surfaces (e.g., iron-sulfide minerals, clay minerals) that may facilitate the reaction. Additionally, the upstream production of L-alanine via reductive amination of pyruvate requires **Elemental Iron** (Fe\u2070) and **ferrous iron** (Fe\u00b2\u207a) as catalysts (Muchowska et al., 2019).\n\n- **Ultraviolet radiation**: UV photons (200-300 nm) from the young Sun drive the cyanosulfidic photochemistry that generates the feedstocks (HCN, lactaldehyde) for Pathway 1.\n\n## 5. Experimental Evidence\n\n### Study 1: Patel et al. (2015)\n- **Title**: \"Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism\"\n- **Journal**: Nature Chemistry\n- **DOI**: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- **Key finding**: Demonstrated that a unified cyanosulfidic chemistry starting from HCN and H2S can produce precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids. For threonine specifically, the paper describes a three-step pathway: (1) HCN cyanohydrin addition to lactaldehyde produces a cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2), (2) amination with ammonia converts the cyanohydrin to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O), and (3) nitrile hydrolysis yields L-threonine with release of ammonia. This is the cyanosulfidic analog of the Strecker synthesis, where the starting aldehyde (lactaldehyde) determines the amino acid product (threonine). The same framework produces glycine (from formaldehyde), alanine (from acetaldehyde), serine (from glycolaldehyde), and valine (from dihydroxyacetone-derived acetone), demonstrating a unified chemical origin for the amino acid repertoire.\n\n### Study 2: Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008)\n- **Title**: \"The Role of Submarine Hydrothermal Systems in the Synthesis of Amino Acids\"\n- **Journal**: Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres\n- **DOI**: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2\n- **Key finding**: Investigated amino acid synthesis under simulated submarine hydrothermal vent conditions. Demonstrated that L-alanine reacts with formaldehyde to produce L-threonine via aldol condensation. This reaction extends the carbon skeleton of a simpler amino acid (alanine, C3) to a more complex one (threonine, C4) by incorporating a C1 unit (formaldehyde). The same study demonstrated the analogous glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation, as well as serine reduction to alanine. These reactions establish a hydrothermal amino acid interconversion network where simpler amino acids serve as building blocks for more complex ones through aldol chemistry with formaldehyde.\n\n## 6. Environmental Context\n\n### Surface Environment (Primary for Pathway 1)\nThe cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015) operates under surface conditions:\n- **Cyanosulfidic nitrile chemistry**: Lactaldehyde reacts with HCN to form a cyanohydrin, which is aminated by ammonia and then hydrolyzed to threonine. This operates in surface pools where HCN-derived chemistry (UV-driven, evaporitic) produces aminonitrile intermediates that hydrolyze in wet phases.\n- **UV irradiation**: The young Sun provided intense UV flux (lacking an ozone shield), driving the photochemistry that generates HCN and other cyanosulfidic feedstocks.\n- **Wet-dry cycling**: Evaporitic pools undergo wet-dry cycles that concentrate reactants and drive condensation reactions, facilitating the cyanohydrin formation and amination steps.\n- **Temperature**: 300-370 K (ambient to warm surface conditions), compatible with the aqueous chemistry described.\n\n### Hydrothermal Environment (Primary for Pathway 2)\nThe aldol condensation pathway (Aubrey et al., 2008) operates under submarine hydrothermal conditions:\n- **L-Alanine availability**: L-alanine is produced by iron-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate at 70\u00b0C (Muchowska et al., 2019), by reduction of L-serine (Aubrey et al., 2008), and by cyanosulfidic aminonitrile hydrolysis (Patel et al., 2015). Multiple upstream pathways feed alanine into the hydrothermal environment.\n- **Formaldehyde availability**: Formaldehyde is produced by hydrothermal reduction of CO2 and by Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on native iron and nickel-iron mineral surfaces. It is a key C1 building block abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids.\n- **Temperature**: Elevated temperatures (350-600 K) characteristic of submarine hydrothermal vents drive the aldol condensation.\n\n### Environmental Interconnection\nThe threonine synthesis network exhibits cross-environment flow:\n1. **Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal**: L-Alanine produced by cyanosulfidic chemistry (Pathway 1-type aminonitrile hydrolysis in surface pools) could be transported to hydrothermal environments, where it undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde (Pathway 2).\n2. **Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface**: Alanine and formaldehyde generated at hydrothermal vents could be transported to surface environments via ocean circulation.\n3. **Parallel independent routes**: The two pathways operate independently in different environments (surface cyanosulfidic vs. hydrothermal aldol), providing robustness to the prebiotic threonine synthesis network.\n4. **Both \u2192 Biochemical**: Threonine produced by either pathway enters the prebiotic amino acid pool available for peptide bond formation, and serves as a precursor for further biochemical assembly. Threonine itself can thermally decompose to glycine under hydrothermal conditions (Vallentyne, 1964; Bada et al., 1978), linking it to the broader amino acid recycling network.\n\n## 7. Open Questions and Challenges\n\n1. **Chirality**: Both demonstrated prebiotic routes produce racemic threonine (equal L and D forms). The origin of homochirality (biological preference for L-amino acids) remains unresolved. Mineral surface adsorption, photolysis with circularly polarized light, or amplification through autocatalytic crystallization have been proposed but not demonstrated specifically for threonine.\n\n2. **Lactaldehyde availability**: Pathway 1 requires lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropionaldehyde), whose prebiotic abundance and stability are debated. It could form from aldol chemistry of simpler aldehydes (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde), from sugar photochemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions, or from reduction of pyruvaldehyde. Quantitative constraints on its steady-state concentration in surface environments are needed.\n\n3. **Threonine thermal stability**: Threonine is thermally labile and decomposes to glycine under hydrothermal conditions (Vallentyne, 1964; Bada et al., 1978). The balance between threonine production (via aldol condensation, Pathway 2) and thermal decomposition at hydrothermal temperatures is a key kinetic question. The retro-aldol decomposition of threonine to glycine (the reverse of the serine-type aldol reaction) may limit threonine accumulation in hydrothermal systems.\n\n4. **2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile stability**: Pathway 1 requires this aminonitrile intermediate to persist long enough for hydrolysis. Its stability under UV irradiation, varying pH, and temperature fluctuations in surface pools needs further study. Competing reactions (polymerization, reaction with other HCN-derived species) could reduce yields.\n\n5. **Formaldehyde concentration**: Pathway 2 requires formaldehyde, which is volatile and reactive. Its prebiotic concentration in hydrothermal environments is debated. Mineral adsorption, continuous production from CO2 reduction via serpentinization-derived H2, and thermophoretic concentration may maintain sufficient steady-state levels.\n\n6. **Alanine as precursor**: Pathway 2 requires L-alanine as a substrate, which must itself be produced by upstream prebiotic reactions. The availability of alanine in sufficient concentrations at hydrothermal vents, where it is simultaneously being consumed by aldol condensation and potentially decomposed at high temperatures, represents a kinetic bottleneck that needs quantitative modeling.\n\n7. **Selectivity and side products**: The aldol condensation of alanine with formaldehyde (Pathway 2) could potentially produce other isomeric products besides threonine. The stereoselectivity and regioselectivity of this reaction under prebiotic conditions, and the relative yields of threonine versus allo-threonine or other isomers, need further characterization.\n\n=== END CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"app