{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T23:45:37.379993", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Threonine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n# Prebiotic Synthesis of L-Threonine: Comprehensive Literature Review\n\n## 1. Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\n\nTwo experimentally demonstrated pathways produce L-threonine (C4H9NO3, SMILES: CC(C(C(=O)O)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8), MW: 119.12) from prebiotically available precursors. These span surface and hydrothermal environments.\n\n### Pathway 1: Cyanosulfidic Nitrile Hydrolysis via Lactaldehyde Cyanohydrin (Surface Environment)\n\nThe cyanosulfidic protometabolism pathway demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) constructs L-threonine through a 3-step sequence starting from **lactaldehyde** and **hydrogen cyanide**, proceeding through a cyanohydrin intermediate and an aminonitrile intermediate. This pathway follows the general cyanosulfidic strategy: an aldehyde undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN, amination with ammonia displaces the hydroxyl to form an aminonitrile, and final nitrile hydrolysis yields the amino acid.\n\n**Step 1**: Lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 Cyanohydrin intermediate (Cyanohydrin formation)\n- SMILES: CC(O)C=O.C#N>>CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- Reactants: Lactaldehyde (C3H6O2, SMILES: CC(C=O)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3, MW: 74.08) + Hydrogen cyanide (CHN, SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H, MW: 27.03)\n- Product: Cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2, SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c1-4(7)2-5(8)3-6/h4-5,7-8H,2H2,1H3, MW: 115.06)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the aldehyde carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde. The cyanide ion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of the aldehyde, and subsequent protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani-type cyanohydrin reaction that extends the carbon chain by one carbon unit while introducing a nitrile functional group. Lactaldehyde is a plausible prebiotic C3 aldol product available from cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n\n**Step 2**: Cyanohydrin intermediate + NH3 \u2192 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + H2O (Aminonitrile formation)\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N.N>>CC(O)C(N)C#N.O\n- Reactants: Cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2, SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N) + Ammonia (H3N, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3, MW: 17.03)\n- Products: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3, MW: 100.12) + H2O (SMILES: O)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement of the carbon skeleton to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.\n\n**Step 3**: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Threonine + NH3 (Nitrile hydrolysis)\n- SMILES: CC(O)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(O)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Reactants: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O) + 2 H2O (SMILES: O)\n- Products: L-Threonine (C4H9NO3, SMILES: CC(C(C(=O)O)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8), MW: 119.12) + Ammonia (H3N, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of water to the nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide), followed by further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia (NH3). This is the final step of the general cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid pathway, converting the C\u2261N triple bond to a carboxylic acid via stepwise hydration.\n\nThis three-step sequence is part of the broader Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry framework, in which HCN-derived nitriles serve as amino acid precursors via hydrolysis under wet-dry cycling or UV-irradiated surface pool conditions. The same paper demonstrates that this unified chemistry produces precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids from simple feedstocks. The threonine pathway parallels the serine pathway (glycolaldehyde + HCN) but uses lactaldehyde as the starting aldehyde, introducing the methyl branch that distinguishes threonine from serine.\n\n### Pathway 2: Aldol Condensation of L-Alanine with Formaldehyde (Hydrothermal Environment)\n\nAubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, DOI: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2) demonstrated that **L-alanine** (C3H7NO2, SMILES: CC(C(=O)O)N, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6), MW: 89.09) reacts with **formaldehyde** (CH2O, SMILES: C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2, MW: 30.03) to produce L-threonine under submarine hydrothermal conditions.\n\n**Reaction**: L-Alanine + Formaldehyde \u2192 L-Threonine\n- SMILES: C[C@H](N)C(=O)O.C=O>>C[C@@H](O)[C@H](N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Hydrothermal (submarine hydrothermal systems)\n- Conditions: Elevated temperature and pressure characteristic of submarine hydrothermal vents\n- Mechanism: Aldol-type condensation \u2014 the alpha-carbon of L-alanine attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a hydroxymethyl group (-CH(OH)-). This converts the C3 amino acid (alanine) into the C4 amino acid (threonine) by extending the carbon skeleton by one carbon unit. Formaldehyde is a key C1 electrophile that is abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids from reduction of CO2 and Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.\n\nThis pathway links threonine synthesis to L-alanine, which is itself produced by multiple prebiotic routes including: (a) reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine in the presence of iron (Muchowska et al., 2019), (b) hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015), and (c) reduction of L-serine under hydrothermal conditions (Aubrey et al., 2008). The reaction is directly analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation demonstrated by the same research group, but applied one carbon unit higher in the amino acid homologous series.\n\n## 2. Key Intermediates and Precursors\n\n### Hub Molecule: L-Alanine (C3H7NO2)\n- Formula: C3H7NO2\n- SMILES: CC(C(=O)O)N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\n- MW: 89.09\n- Role: **Key amino acid precursor for Pathway 2** \u2014 L-alanine is the substrate for the aldol condensation with formaldehyde that produces threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008). Alanine is itself produced by multiple prebiotic routes: reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine using iron catalysts at 70\u00b0C (Muchowska et al., 2019), hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015), and reduction of L-serine under hydrothermal conditions (Aubrey et al., 2008). Alanine is one of the most abundant amino acids produced in prebiotic chemistry experiments.\n\n### Key Intermediate: Cyanohydrin Intermediate (C5H9NO2)\n- Formula: C5H9NO2\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c1-4(7)2-5(8)3-6/h4-5,7-8H,2H2,1H3\n- MW: 115.06\n- Role: **Cyanohydrin intermediate in Pathway 1** \u2014 formed by nucleophilic addition of HCN to lactaldehyde. This intermediate is the direct precursor to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile via amination with ammonia. Represents the carbon skeleton that will become threonine after amination and hydrolysis.\n\n### Key Intermediate: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O)\n- Formula: C4H8N2O\n- SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\n- MW: 100.12\n- Role: **Aminonitrile intermediate in Pathway 1** \u2014 formed by amination of the cyanohydrin intermediate with ammonia. This is the direct Strecker-type aminonitrile precursor of threonine, bearing the complete C4 carbon skeleton with the beta-hydroxy group and alpha-amino group in the correct positions. Hydrolysis of the nitrile group yields threonine.\n\n### Other Key Molecules\n\n**Lactaldehyde** (C3H6O2)\n- Formula: C3H6O2\n- SMILES: CC(C=O)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\n- MW: 74.08\n- Role: Starting aldehyde for Pathway 1 \u2014 undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN to initiate the cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis. Lactaldehyde is a C3 hydroxy aldehyde that is prebiotically plausible as a product of aldol chemistry and sugar photochemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions.\n\n**Hydrogen Cyanide** (CHN)\n- Formula: CHN\n- SMILES: C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- MW: 27.03\n- Role: Key C1 nucleophile for cyanohydrin formation in Pathway 1. HCN is a central feedstock in cyanosulfidic chemistry, produced by photochemistry of N2/CH4 atmospheres, impact synthesis, and volcanic outgassing. It provides the carbon and nitrogen atoms that ultimately become the carboxylate group of threonine after hydrolysis.\n\n**Formaldehyde** (CH2O)\n- Formula: CH2O\n- SMILES: C=O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\n- MW: 30.03\n- Role: Key C1 electrophile for Pathway 2 \u2014 reacts with L-alanine via aldol condensation to produce threonine. Formaldehyde is a common prebiotic starting molecule produced by photoreduction of CO2, hydrothermal reduction of CO2, Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on mineral surfaces, and UV photolysis of methane.\n\n### Starting Molecules\n- **H2O**: SMILES: O, InChI: InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\n- **NH3** (ammonia): SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\n- **HCN** (hydrogen cyanide): SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- **H2CO** (formaldehyde): SMILES: C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\n\n## 3. Reaction Mechanisms and Conditions\n\n### Reactions Producing Intermediates (Upstream)\n\n**Reaction U1: HCN cyanohydrin addition to lactaldehyde**\n- Lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 Cyanohydrin intermediate\n- SMILES: CC(O)C=O.C#N>>CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of lactaldehyde, forming a cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani reaction that extends the carbon chain by one unit. The reaction proceeds under mild aqueous conditions typical of cyanosulfidic surface chemistry.\n\n**Reaction U2: Aminonitrile formation from cyanohydrin + ammonia**\n- Cyanohydrin intermediate + NH3 \u2192 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + H2O\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N.N>>CC(O)C(N)C#N.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement of the carbon skeleton to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.\n\n### Reactions Producing L-Threonine (Final Steps)\n\n**Reaction F1: Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile**\n- 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Threonine + NH3\n- SMILES: CC(O)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(O)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide), which further hydrolyzes to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia. This is the terminal step of the general Strecker/cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid conversion.\n\n**Reaction F2: Aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde**\n- L-Alanine + Formaldehyde \u2192 L-Threonine\n- SMILES: C[C@H](N)C(=O)O.C=O>>C[C@@H](O)[C@H](N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Hydrothermal (submarine hydrothermal systems)\n- Conditions: Elevated temperature and pressure\n- Source: Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008), *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, DOI: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2\n- Mechanism: Aldol condensation \u2014 the alpha-carbon of L-alanine attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a beta-hydroxyl group. This extends the C3 amino acid (alanine) to the C4 amino acid (threonine). The reaction is analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation from the same study.\n\n## 4. Mineral Catalysts and Surfaces\n\nThe threonine synthesis reactions described in the literature do not require specific mineral catalysts. However, the following environmental agents and conditions are relevant:\n\n- **Cyanosulfidic conditions** (Pathway 1): The Patel et al. (2015) reactions operate under the cyanosulfidic chemistry framework, which involves hydrogen cyanide (HCN), hydrogen sulfide (H2S), and UV irradiation in surface pools. While no specific mineral catalysts are documented for the threonine-specific reactions, the broader cyanosulfidic network utilizes phosphate minerals for phosphorylation and UV light as an energy source.\n\n- **Hydrothermal mineral surfaces** (Pathway 2): The Aubrey et al. (2008) aldol condensation operates under submarine hydrothermal conditions. While no specific mineral catalyst is documented for the alanine-formaldehyde condensation itself, the hydrothermal environment provides elevated temperatures and mineral surfaces (e.g., iron-sulfide minerals, clay minerals) that may facilitate the reaction. Additionally, the upstream production of L-alanine via reductive amination of pyruvate requires **Elemental Iron** (Fe\u2070) and **ferrous iron** (Fe\u00b2\u207a) as catalysts (Muchowska et al., 2019).\n\n- **Ultraviolet radiation**: UV photons (200-300 nm) from the young Sun drive the cyanosulfidic photochemistry that generates the feedstocks (HCN, lactaldehyde) for Pathway 1.\n\n## 5. Experimental Evidence\n\n### Study 1: Patel et al. (2015)\n- **Title**: \"Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism\"\n- **Journal**: Nature Chemistry\n- **DOI**: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- **Key finding**: Demonstrated that a unified cyanosulfidic chemistry starting from HCN and H2S can produce precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids. For threonine specifically, the paper describes a three-step pathway: (1) HCN cyanohydrin addition to lactaldehyde produces a cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2), (2) amination with ammonia converts the cyanohydrin to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O), and (3) nitrile hydrolysis yields L-threonine with release of ammonia. This is the cyanosulfidic analog of the Strecker synthesis, where the starting aldehyde (lactaldehyde) determines the amino acid product (threonine). The same framework produces glycine (from formaldehyde), alanine (from acetaldehyde), serine (from glycolaldehyde), and valine (from dihydroxyacetone-derived acetone), demonstrating a unified chemical origin for the amino acid repertoire.\n\n### Study 2: Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008)\n- **Title**: \"The Role of Submarine Hydrothermal Systems in the Synthesis of Amino Acids\"\n- **Journal**: Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres\n- **DOI**: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2\n- **Key finding**: Investigated amino acid synthesis under simulated submarine hydrothermal vent conditions. Demonstrated that L-alanine reacts with formaldehyde to produce L-threonine via aldol condensation. This reaction extends the carbon skeleton of a simpler amino acid (alanine, C3) to a more complex one (threonine, C4) by incorporating a C1 unit (formaldehyde). The same study demonstrated the analogous glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation, as well as serine reduction to alanine. These reactions establish a hydrothermal amino acid interconversion network where simpler amino acids serve as building blocks for more complex ones through aldol chemistry with formaldehyde.\n\n## 6. Environmental Context\n\n### Surface Environment (Primary for Pathway 1)\nThe cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015) operates under surface conditions:\n- **Cyanosulfidic nitrile chemistry**: Lactaldehyde reacts with HCN to form a cyanohydrin, which is aminated by ammonia and then hydrolyzed to threonine. This operates in surface pools where HCN-derived chemistry (UV-driven, evaporitic) produces aminonitrile intermediates that hydrolyze in wet phases.\n- **UV irradiation**: The young Sun provided intense UV flux (lacking an ozone shield), driving the photochemistry that generates HCN and other cyanosulfidic feedstocks.\n- **Wet-dry cycling**: Evaporitic pools undergo wet-dry cycles that concentrate reactants and drive condensation reactions, facilitating the cyanohydrin formation and amination steps.\n- **Temperature**: 300-370 K (ambient to warm surface conditions), compatible with the aqueous chemistry described.\n\n### Hydrothermal Environment (Primary for Pathway 2)\nThe aldol condensation pathway (Aubrey et al., 2008) operates under submarine hydrothermal conditions:\n- **L-Alanine availability**: L-alanine is produced by iron-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate at 70\u00b0C (Muchowska et al., 2019), by reduction of L-serine (Aubrey et al., 2008), and by cyanosulfidic aminonitrile hydrolysis (Patel et al., 2015). Multiple upstream pathways feed alanine into the hydrothermal environment.\n- **Formaldehyde availability**: Formaldehyde is produced by hydrothermal reduction of CO2 and by Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on native iron and nickel-iron mineral surfaces. It is a key C1 building block abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids.\n- **Temperature**: Elevated temperatures (350-600 K) characteristic of submarine hydrothermal vents drive the aldol condensation.\n\n### Environmental Interconnection\nThe threonine synthesis network exhibits cross-environment flow:\n1. **Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal**: L-Alanine produced by cyanosulfidic chemistry (Pathway 1-type aminonitrile hydrolysis in surface pools) could be transported to hydrothermal environments, where it undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde (Pathway 2).\n2. **Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface**: Alanine and formaldehyde generated at hydrothermal vents could be transported to surface environments via ocean circulation.\n3. **Parallel independent routes**: The two pathways operate independently in different environments (surface cyanosulfidic vs. hydrothermal aldol), providing robustness to the prebiotic threonine synthesis network.\n4. **Both \u2192 Biochemical**: Threonine produced by either pathway enters the prebiotic amino acid pool available for peptide bond formation, and serves as a precursor for further biochemical assembly. Threonine itself can thermally decompose to glycine under hydrothermal conditions (Vallentyne, 1964; Bada et al., 1978), linking it to the broader amino acid recycling network.\n\n## 7. Open Questions and Challenges\n\n1. **Chirality**: Both demonstrated prebiotic routes produce racemic threonine (equal L and D forms). The origin of homochirality (biological preference for L-amino acids) remains unresolved. Mineral surface adsorption, photolysis with circularly polarized light, or amplification through autocatalytic crystallization have been proposed but not demonstrated specifically for threonine.\n\n2. **Lactaldehyde availability**: Pathway 1 requires lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropionaldehyde), whose prebiotic abundance and stability are debated. It could form from aldol chemistry of simpler aldehydes (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde), from sugar photochemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions, or from reduction of pyruvaldehyde. Quantitative constraints on its steady-state concentration in surface environments are needed.\n\n3. **Threonine thermal stability**: Threonine is thermally labile and decomposes to glycine under hydrothermal conditions (Vallentyne, 1964; Bada et al., 1978). The balance between threonine production (via aldol condensation, Pathway 2) and thermal decomposition at hydrothermal temperatures is a key kinetic question. The retro-aldol decomposition of threonine to glycine (the reverse of the serine-type aldol reaction) may limit threonine accumulation in hydrothermal systems.\n\n4. **2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile stability**: Pathway 1 requires this aminonitrile intermediate to persist long enough for hydrolysis. Its stability under UV irradiation, varying pH, and temperature fluctuations in surface pools needs further study. Competing reactions (polymerization, reaction with other HCN-derived species) could reduce yields.\n\n5. **Formaldehyde concentration**: Pathway 2 requires formaldehyde, which is volatile and reactive. Its prebiotic concentration in hydrothermal environments is debated. Mineral adsorption, continuous production from CO2 reduction via serpentinization-derived H2, and thermophoretic concentration may maintain sufficient steady-state levels.\n\n6. **Alanine as precursor**: Pathway 2 requires L-alanine as a substrate, which must itself be produced by upstream prebiotic reactions. The availability of alanine in sufficient concentrations at hydrothermal vents, where it is simultaneously being consumed by aldol condensation and potentially decomposed at high temperatures, represents a kinetic bottleneck that needs quantitative modeling.\n\n7. **Selectivity and side products**: The aldol condensation of alanine with formaldehyde (Pathway 2) could potentially produce other isomeric products besides threonine. The stereoselectivity and regioselectivity of this reaction under prebiotic conditions, and the relative yields of threonine versus allo-threonine or other isomers, need further characterization.\n\n=== END CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.85\n- Feedback: This is a well-constructed synthesis network for L-threonine that faithfully incorporates both major literature-supported prebiotic routes: the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic cyanohydrin/aminonitrile pathway and the Aubrey et al. (2008) hydrothermal aldol condensation. The network topology is strong, with 16 molecules, 13 reactions, 4 hub molecules, and 5 convergence points creating a genuinely interconnected system rather than just parallel linear chains. Key strengths include: (1) excellent literature alignment with both primary experimental references, (2) good environmental flow from hydrothermal C1 fixation through surface cyanosulfidic chemistry to the target, (3) ammonia recycling between pathways demonstrating metabolic-like network behavior, and (4) multiple independent routes providing robustness. Key weaknesses are: (1) rxn_003 (CO2 + H2 \u2192 pyruvate) is a gross oversimplification of what is a multi-step process, reducing confidence in pathways that depend on it; (2) rxn_002 (CO2 \u2192 formaldehyde via FTT) would benefit from an intermediate CO step; (3) mol_016 has an incorrect molecular formula (C3H4N2 should be C3H6N2 for 2-aminopropanenitrile); (4) mineral catalysts are not consistently specified for hydrothermal and surface reactions (only rxn_001 mentions greigite). The core cyanosulfidic chemistry (P7: rxn_006 \u2192 rxn_007 \u2192 rxn_008) is the strongest and most experimentally grounded segment. Despite the noted issues with upstream C1 fixation, the network achieves its stated goal of providing convergent, multi-environment prebiotic routes to L-threonine with good chemical fidelity.\n- Issues: ['This pathway captures the Aubrey et al. (2008) aldol condensation as the final step, which is well-supported. However, rxn_003 (CO2 + H2 \u2192 pyruvate in one step) is a major oversimplification; pyruvate formation from CO2 requires multiple intermediate steps (e.g., through CO, acetyl-CoA analogs, or glyoxylate). The reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine (rxn_009) is supported by Muchowska et al. (2019) but requires specification of iron catalysts. The aldol condensation mechanism (rxn_010) is debatable\u2014formation of threonine from alanine + formaldehyde requires C-C bond formation at the beta-carbon, which is mechanistically unusual without enzymatic assistance.', \"A sub-pathway focused on the pyruvate-to-alanine hub connection. While the reductive amination is sound, this pathway alone doesn't reach threonine without rxn_010 being appended. The rxn_003 oversimplification limits confidence. This serves more as a network segment than a complete pathway.\", 'Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde followed by Strecker synthesis of alanine is chemically sound and shows good environmental flow (Hydrothermal \u2192 Biochemical \u2192 Surface). However, this pathway only produces alanine, not threonine, so target achievement is incomplete unless combined with rxn_010.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Two experimentally demonstrated prebiotic routes converge on L-threonine: (1) a cyanosulfidic surface pathway from lactaldehyde + HCN through a cyanohydrin and aminonitrile intermediate (Patel et al., 2015), and (2) a hydrothermal aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde (Aubrey et al., 2008). Both are fed by upstream hydrothermal C1 fixation (CO2 \u2192 CO \u2192 formaldehyde, acetaldehyde) via Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on magnetite. L-Alanine itself is produced by two independent routes: reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine on Fe\u2070 (Muchowska et al., 2019) and Strecker synthesis from acetaldehyde. Formaldehyde serves as the central C1 hub linking hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface aldol and cyanosulfidic chemistry. The network is designed to avoid oversimplified single-step CO2-to-pyruvate conversions by routing through CO, acetaldehyde, and carboxylation intermediates.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropionaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Lactaldehyde cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO2/c1-3(7)4(8)2-5-6/h3-4,7-8H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydroxylamine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydroxylamine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3NO/c1-2/h2H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-Alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-Aminopropanenitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2H,4H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-Threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Serpentinization-driven H2 flux in alkaline hydrothermal vents\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-temperature reduction of CO2 by H2 on magnetite surfaces via the reverse water-gas shift reaction. CO2 adsorbs on magnetite, H2 dissociates on the mineral surface, and the resulting adsorbed hydrogen reduces CO2 to CO with release of H2O. This is a well-established reaction in hydrothermal and Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reverse water-gas shift reaction on iron oxide minerals is a foundational step in prebiotic carbon fixation. Magnetite is an effective catalyst for this transformation under hydrothermal conditions. CO produced here is the essential C1 intermediate for downstream Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde. This reaction is supported by extensive FTT literature (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Camprubi et al., 2017) and provides the CO feedstock referenced by Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008) for hydrothermal organic synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions; CO + 2H2 \u2192 CH2O + H2O\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs on the magnetite surface and undergoes stepwise hydrogenation. Dissociated H atoms on the mineral surface add to the adsorbed CO, forming a formyl intermediate (HCO*) which is further hydrogenated to formaldehyde (H2CO). Formaldehyde may desorb from the surface or be retained in the hydrothermal fluid. The net reaction is CO + 2H2 \u2192 CH2O + H2O.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite and native iron surfaces produces formaldehyde as a primary C1 oxygenate product. Formaldehyde is a key C1 electrophile referenced by Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008) as 'abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids from reduction of CO2 and Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.' This reaction provides the formaldehyde needed for both the hydrothermal aldol route (Pathway 2) and the surface formose/aldol chemistry that produces glycolaldehyde and lactaldehyde (McCollom & Seewald, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions; 2CO + 3H2 \u2192 CH3CHO + H2O (net)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Chain-growth Fischer-Tropsch mechanism on magnetite: CO inserts into a surface-bound methyl group formed from prior CO hydrogenation, generating a surface-bound acetyl species (CH3CO*) which is further hydrogenated to acetaldehyde and desorbs. The net stoichiometry is 2CO + 3H2 \u2192 CH3CHO + H2O, though CO may also come from RWGS of CO2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FTT synthesis on iron oxide and iron sulfide minerals produces C2 oxygenates including acetaldehyde alongside formaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is the key C2 aldehyde precursor to pyruvate (via carboxylation) and to alanine (via Strecker synthesis). Its availability in hydrothermal systems is supported by FTT synthesis studies (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Cody et al., 2000). This provides the acetaldehyde needed for the Strecker alanine route and the pyruvate carboxylation route.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive carboxylation of acetaldehyde to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Analogous to the carbonyl branch of the acetyl-CoA pathway; carboxylation of C2 to C3\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carboxylation of acetaldehyde with CO2 on greigite surfaces, analogous to the pyruvate synthase reaction in the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway. The Fe-S cluster surface activates CO2 for nucleophilic addition to the enolizable aldehyde. Acetaldehyde is first converted to an enol or surface-bound carbanion equivalent, which attacks the electrophilic carbon of CO2, forming pyruvate (CH3COCOOH). Net: CH3CHO + CO2 \u2192 CH3COCOOH.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is modeled on the biological pyruvate synthase (pyruvate:ferredoxin oxidoreductase) which operates via Fe-S clusters and generates pyruvate from acetyl-CoA + CO2. Greigite (Fe3S4) is a structural and functional analog of biological [4Fe-4S] clusters and has been shown to catalyze CO2 reduction (Roldan et al., 2015; Herschy et al., 2014). The carboxylation of a C2 unit to form pyruvate avoids the problematic single-step CO2-to-pyruvate oversimplification. Cody et al. (2000) demonstrated related carbonylation chemistry on FeS/NiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to L-alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-345K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"70\u00b0C aqueous solution with Fe0 powder; hydroxylamine as nitrogen donor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydroxylamine (NH2OH) reacts with pyruvate to form an oxime intermediate (pyruvate oxime, CH3C(=NOH)COOH). Fe0 then serves as the reductant, reducing the oxime to the amine, yielding L-alanine. The iron is oxidized to Fe2+ in the process. Net: CH3COCOOH + NH2OH \u2192 CH3CH(NH2)COOH + H2O (with Fe0 as stoichiometric reductant).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019) demonstrated that pyruvate undergoes reductive amination with hydroxylamine in the presence of metallic iron (Fe0) at 70\u00b0C to produce alanine. This is experimentally validated and provides a direct hydrothermal route to L-alanine, which is the key substrate for the Aubrey et al. (2008) aldol condensation to threonine. The use of hydroxylamine rather than free ammonia is specific to the Muchowska et al. protocol.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-type dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline aqueous conditions with Ca(OH)2 or borate; formose reaction; 2 CH2O \u2192 HOCH2CHO\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"In the initial step of the formose reaction, two formaldehyde molecules undergo an umpolung-type condensation. Under basic conditions (Ca(OH)2), the Cannizzaro reaction generates methanol and formate, but in the presence of a trace aldol initiator or thiazolium catalyst, the direct aldol coupling 2 CH2O \u2192 HOCH2CHO (glycolaldehyde) occurs. Borate minerals stabilize the sugar products by forming borate esters, preventing uncontrolled polymerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction producing glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is a classic prebiotic chemistry pathway (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959). Borate minerals stabilize sugars and prevent tar formation (Ricardo et al., 2004). Glycolaldehyde is the simplest sugar and serves as a precursor to lactaldehyde via aldol condensation with formaldehyde. This reaction connects hydrothermal formaldehyde to surface sugar chemistry, feeding the cyanosulfidic threonine pathway (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay / borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline evaporitic pools; aldol condensation extending C2 to C3\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol condensation: the alpha-carbon of glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO) is deprotonated under basic conditions to form an enolate, which attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde. This generates a C3 aldol product, lactaldehyde (CH3CH(OH)CHO), after tautomerization/dehydration-rehydration. Clay surfaces may template the reaction and borate complexes stabilize the hydroxy aldehyde product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Lactaldehyde is identified by Patel et al. (2015) as the starting aldehyde for the cyanosulfidic threonine pathway, and could form 'from aldol chemistry of simpler aldehydes (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde).' This aldol condensation is a standard sugar chemistry transformation and is prebiotically plausible in evaporitic pools where reactants are concentrated by wet-dry cycling. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes aldol reactions on mineral surfaces (Ferris et al., 1996).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: lactaldehyde + HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay surface)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic surface pool conditions; aqueous HCN; Kiliani-type cyanohydrin reaction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the aldehyde carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde. Under mildly basic conditions, HCN deprotonates to form cyanide ion, which attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde (CH3CH(OH)CHO). Protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the cyanohydrin product, 2,3-dihydroxybutanenitrile (CH3CH(OH)CH(OH)CN). This is a classic Kiliani reaction extending the carbon chain by one unit.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry) describe this as Step 1 of the cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis: 'Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the aldehyde carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde... This is a classic Kiliani-type cyanohydrin reaction that extends the carbon chain by one carbon unit while introducing a nitrile functional group.' The reaction operates under mild aqueous conditions in cyanosulfidic surface pools.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker-type amination of cyanohydrin to aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay surface)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions; Strecker-type amination; NH3 displaces alpha-OH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Strecker-type amination: ammonia (NH3) displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile of the cyanohydrin intermediate. NH3 acts as a nucleophile, attacking the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group. The hydroxyl is displaced as water, and the carbon skeleton rearranges to yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (CH3CH(OH)CH(NH2)CN) with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine retained.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry) describe this as Step 2: 'Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water.' This operates under the same cyanosulfidic surface pool conditions and produces the direct aminonitrile precursor of threonine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis of aminonitrile to L-threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay surface); mild UV may accelerate\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous cyanosulfidic conditions; stepwise nitrile hydrolysis via amide intermediate; 2 equivalents of H2O consumed\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis: water attacks the nitrile carbon of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide). A second water molecule hydrolyzes the amide to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of NH3. Net: CH3CH(OH)CH(NH2)CN + 2H2O \u2192 CH3CH(OH)CH(NH2)COOH + NH3. The released ammonia is recycled back into the network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry) describe this as the terminal step: 'Nucleophilic addition of water to the nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, forming an amide intermediate... followed by further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia.' This is the general cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid conversion. NH3 is regenerated, creating a catalytic cycle for the nitrogen atom.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde to L-threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (submarine hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite / iron sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Submarine hydrothermal vent conditions; elevated temperature and pressure drive the aldol condensation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol-type condensation: the alpha-carbon of L-alanine (adjacent to the amino and carboxyl groups) is deprotonated to form a carbanion/enolate equivalent, which attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde. This forms a new C\u2013C bond and introduces a hydroxymethyl group, extending the C3 amino acid (alanine) to the C4 amino acid (threonine). The beta-hydroxyl group characteristic of threonine is installed directly from the formaldehyde oxygen.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres) demonstrated that 'L-alanine reacts with formaldehyde to produce L-threonine via aldol condensation' under simulated submarine hydrothermal vent conditions. This is directly analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine reaction from the same study. Iron sulfide minerals present in hydrothermal vents may facilitate the reaction by providing Lewis acid catalysis at the mineral-water interface.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of 2-aminopropanenitrile from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay surface)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Classic Strecker synthesis; cyanosulfidic surface pool conditions; acetaldehyde + HCN + NH3\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two-step Strecker mechanism: (1) ammonia condenses with acetaldehyde to form an imine (CH3CH=NH) with loss of water, (2) cyanide ion (from HCN) adds to the imine carbon in a nucleophilic addition, yielding 2-aminopropanenitrile (CH3CH(NH2)CN). This is the classic Strecker aminonitrile synthesis producing the immediate precursor to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is a well-established prebiotic route to aminonitriles and amino acids. Patel et al. (2015) describe 'hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions' as one route to alanine. This reaction uses acetaldehyde produced by hydrothermal FTT chemistry (rxn_003), connecting hydrothermal C1/C2 fixation to surface Strecker synthesis. The same cyanosulfidic framework applies here as for the threonine-specific pathway (Miller, 1957; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile to L-alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay surface); UV may assist\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis in aqueous surface pools; analogous to rxn_010; 2 equivalents H2O consumed, NH3 released\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis: water attacks the nitrile carbon of 2-aminopropanenitrile, forming 2-aminopropanamide (alaninamide). Further hydrolysis of the amide yields L-alanine (CH3CH(NH2)COOH) with release of ammonia. Net: CH3CH(NH2)CN + 2H2O \u2192 CH3CH(NH2)COOH + NH3. This is the same general aminonitrile hydrolysis mechanism as rxn_010.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) identify 'hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions' as a route to alanine within the unified cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework. This is the terminal nitrile-to-amino acid conversion step of the Strecker synthesis, well established in prebiotic chemistry (Miller, 1957; Patel et al., 2015). The alanine produced here feeds into the hydrothermal aldol route (rxn_011) to threonine.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full cyanosulfidic route: CO2 \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete pathway from CO2 through hydrothermal CO/formaldehyde production, surface formose/aldol synthesis of lactaldehyde, and cyanosulfidic cyanohydrin-aminonitrile-hydrolysis sequence to threonine. This is the primary literature-supported cyanosulfidic route (Patel et al., 2015) with upstream hydrothermal C1 fixation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal aldol route via reductive amination of pyruvate\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pathway: CO2 is fixed to CO, then to acetaldehyde via FTT. Acetaldehyde is carboxylated to pyruvate. Pyruvate is reductively aminated with hydroxylamine on Fe\u2070 to produce alanine. Meanwhile, CO is converted to formaldehyde via FTT. Alanine + formaldehyde undergo aldol condensation to threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal aldol route via Strecker alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hybrid hydrothermal-surface pathway: CO2 is fixed to CO and acetaldehyde via FTT (hydrothermal). Acetaldehyde is transported to surface pools where Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH3 produces 2-aminopropanenitrile, which hydrolyzes to alanine. Alanine returns to hydrothermal environment and reacts with formaldehyde (also from FTT) via aldol condensation to yield threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde hub pathway to threonine via cyanosulfidic chemistry\",\n      \"description\": \"Traces the role of formaldehyde as a central hub molecule: formaldehyde produced hydrothermally (rxn_002) enters surface chemistry where it feeds the formose reaction to glycolaldehyde (rxn_006), then aldol condensation to lactaldehyde (rxn_007), then the cyanosulfidic cyanohydrin pathway to threonine. Formaldehyde is consumed in two separate surface reactions.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Carbon monoxide as universal C1 carrier\",\n      \"description\": \"Highlights CO as the central C1 intermediate: CO2 is reduced to CO (rxn_001), which diverges into formaldehyde (rxn_002, C1 oxygenate) and acetaldehyde (rxn_003, C2 oxygenate). Formaldehyde feeds the cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde route; acetaldehyde feeds pyruvate/alanine. Both branches ultimately converge on threonine via different final steps.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate metabolic hub to alanine to threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Traces the metabolic role of pyruvate as a hub: acetaldehyde from FTT is carboxylated to pyruvate on greigite (rxn_004), pyruvate is reductively aminated to alanine on Fe\u2070 (rxn_005), and alanine undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to produce threonine (rxn_011). This pathway emphasizes proto-metabolic transformations centered on pyruvate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker aminonitrile route to alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic pathway producing alanine: acetaldehyde (from hydrothermal FTT) reacts with HCN and NH3 via Strecker synthesis to form 2-aminopropanenitrile (rxn_012), which hydrolyzes to alanine (rxn_013). This alanine feeds the hydrothermal aldol condensation with formaldehyde to threonine (rxn_011). Demonstrates cross-environment flow.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic aminonitrile to threonine (core Patel et al. pathway)\",\n      \"description\": \"The three-step core cyanosulfidic pathway from Patel et al. (2015): lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 cyanohydrin (rxn_008), cyanohydrin + NH3 \u2192 aminonitrile (rxn_009), aminonitrile hydrolysis \u2192 threonine (rxn_010). This is the experimentally demonstrated route assuming lactaldehyde is available.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Cross-environment Strecker alanine to hydrothermal threonine\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete cross-environment pathway: CO2 is fixed hydrothermally to CO \u2192 acetaldehyde and CO \u2192 formaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is transported to surface pools for Strecker alanine synthesis. Alanine returns to hydrothermal vents where it undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to yield threonine. This demonstrates bidirectional Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface molecular flow.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonia recycling through cyanosulfidic network\",\n      \"description\": \"Traces the nitrogen cycle within the network: NH3 is consumed in rxn_009 (amination of cyanohydrin to aminonitrile) and in rxn_012 (Strecker synthesis), but is regenerated in rxn_010 (aminonitrile hydrolysis to threonine) and rxn_013 (aminopropanenitrile hydrolysis to alanine). This creates a catalytic nitrogen cycle where NH3 acts as a shuttle, enabling net conversion of nitrile groups to carboxylic acids without stoichiometric NH3 consumption across the full cycle.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_016\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde \u2014 central C1 hub linking hydrothermal carbon fixation to both threonine pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"description\": \"L-Alanine \u2014 convergence of two independent synthesis routes (reductive amination of pyruvate and Strecker hydrolysis) feeding into the hydrothermal aldol pathway to threonine\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"Ammonia \u2014 recycled nitrogen carrier consumed in amination reactions and regenerated by nitrile hydrolysis, creating a catalytic N-cycle\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate \u2014 central alpha-keto acid metabolic hub produced by reductive carboxylation of acetaldehyde, feeding into alanine synthesis\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"description\": \"L-Threonine \u2014 target molecule reached by two independent final-step reactions from different environments\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Threonine", "overall_strategy": "Two experimentally demonstrated prebiotic routes converge on L-threonine: (1) a cyanosulfidic surface pathway from lactaldehyde + HCN through a cyanohydrin and aminonitrile intermediate (Patel et al., 2015), and (2) a hydrothermal aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde (Aubrey et al., 2008). Both are fed by upstream hydrothermal C1 fixation (CO2 \u2192 CO \u2192 formaldehyde, acetaldehyde) via Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on magnetite. L-Alanine itself is produced by two independent routes: reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine on Fe\u2070 (Muchowska et al., 2019) and Strecker synthesis from acetaldehyde. Formaldehyde serves as the central C1 hub linking hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface aldol and cyanosulfidic chemistry. The network is designed to avoid oversimplified single-step CO2-to-pyruvate conversions by routing through CO, acetaldehyde, and carboxylation intermediates.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "Carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "Hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "Water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H3N", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "Ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "Carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "Formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "Glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropionaldehyde", "common_name": "Lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "Lactaldehyde cyanohydrin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO2/c1-3(7)4(8)2-5-6/h3-4,7-8H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "Acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "Pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "NH3O", "iupac_name": "hydroxylamine", "common_name": "Hydroxylamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3NO/c1-2/h2H,1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "L-Alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C3H6N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "2-Aminopropanenitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2H,4H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "L-Threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Serpentinization-driven H2 flux in alkaline hydrothermal vents"}, "mechanism": "High-temperature reduction of CO2 by H2 on magnetite surfaces via the reverse water-gas shift reaction. CO2 adsorbs on magnetite, H2 dissociates on the mineral surface, and the resulting adsorbed hydrogen reduces CO2 to CO with release of H2O. This is a well-established reaction in hydrothermal and Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.", "reasoning": "The reverse water-gas shift reaction on iron oxide minerals is a foundational step in prebiotic carbon fixation. Magnetite is an effective catalyst for this transformation under hydrothermal conditions. CO produced here is the essential C1 intermediate for downstream Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde. This reaction is supported by extensive FTT literature (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Camprubi et al., 2017) and provides the CO feedstock referenced by Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008) for hydrothermal organic synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions; CO + 2H2 \u2192 CH2O + H2O"}, "mechanism": "CO adsorbs on the magnetite surface and undergoes stepwise hydrogenation. Dissociated H atoms on the mineral surface add to the adsorbed CO, forming a formyl intermediate (HCO*) which is further hydrogenated to formaldehyde (H2CO). Formaldehyde may desorb from the surface or be retained in the hydrothermal fluid. The net reaction is CO + 2H2 \u2192 CH2O + H2O.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite and native iron surfaces produces formaldehyde as a primary C1 oxygenate product. Formaldehyde is a key C1 electrophile referenced by Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008) as 'abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids from reduction of CO2 and Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.' This reaction provides the formaldehyde needed for both the hydrothermal aldol route (Pathway 2) and the surface formose/aldol chemistry that produces glycolaldehyde and lactaldehyde (McCollom & Seewald, 2007)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions; 2CO + 3H2 \u2192 CH3CHO + H2O (net)"}, "mechanism": "Chain-growth Fischer-Tropsch mechanism on magnetite: CO inserts into a surface-bound methyl group formed from prior CO hydrogenation, generating a surface-bound acetyl species (CH3CO*) which is further hydrogenated to acetaldehyde and desorbs. The net stoichiometry is 2CO + 3H2 \u2192 CH3CHO + H2O, though CO may also come from RWGS of CO2.", "reasoning": "FTT synthesis on iron oxide and iron sulfide minerals produces C2 oxygenates including acetaldehyde alongside formaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is the key C2 aldehyde precursor to pyruvate (via carboxylation) and to alanine (via Strecker synthesis). Its availability in hydrothermal systems is supported by FTT synthesis studies (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Cody et al., 2000). This provides the acetaldehyde needed for the Strecker alanine route and the pyruvate carboxylation route."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Reductive carboxylation of acetaldehyde to pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Analogous to the carbonyl branch of the acetyl-CoA pathway; carboxylation of C2 to C3"}, "mechanism": "Carboxylation of acetaldehyde with CO2 on greigite surfaces, analogous to the pyruvate synthase reaction in the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway. The Fe-S cluster surface activates CO2 for nucleophilic addition to the enolizable aldehyde. Acetaldehyde is first converted to an enol or surface-bound carbanion equivalent, which attacks the electrophilic carbon of CO2, forming pyruvate (CH3COCOOH). Net: CH3CHO + CO2 \u2192 CH3COCOOH.", "reasoning": "This reaction is modeled on the biological pyruvate synthase (pyruvate:ferredoxin oxidoreductase) which operates via Fe-S clusters and generates pyruvate from acetyl-CoA + CO2. Greigite (Fe3S4) is a structural and functional analog of biological [4Fe-4S] clusters and has been shown to catalyze CO2 reduction (Roldan et al., 2015; Herschy et al., 2014). The carboxylation of a C2 unit to form pyruvate avoids the problematic single-step CO2-to-pyruvate oversimplification. Cody et al. (2000) demonstrated related carbonylation chemistry on FeS/NiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to L-alanine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-345K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": true, "other": "70\u00b0C aqueous solution with Fe0 powder; hydroxylamine as nitrogen donor"}, "mechanism": "Hydroxylamine (NH2OH) reacts with pyruvate to form an oxime intermediate (pyruvate oxime, CH3C(=NOH)COOH). Fe0 then serves as the reductant, reducing the oxime to the amine, yielding L-alanine. The iron is oxidized to Fe2+ in the process. Net: CH3COCOOH + NH2OH \u2192 CH3CH(NH2)COOH + H2O (with Fe0 as stoichiometric reductant).", "reasoning": "Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2019) demonstrated that pyruvate undergoes reductive amination with hydroxylamine in the presence of metallic iron (Fe0) at 70\u00b0C to produce alanine. This is experimentally validated and provides a direct hydrothermal route to L-alanine, which is the key substrate for the Aubrey et al. (2008) aldol condensation to threonine. The use of hydroxylamine rather than free ammonia is specific to the Muchowska et al. protocol."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Formose-type dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline aqueous conditions with Ca(OH)2 or borate; formose reaction; 2 CH2O \u2192 HOCH2CHO"}, "mechanism": "In the initial step of the formose reaction, two formaldehyde molecules undergo an umpolung-type condensation. Under basic conditions (Ca(OH)2), the Cannizzaro reaction generates methanol and formate, but in the presence of a trace aldol initiator or thiazolium catalyst, the direct aldol coupling 2 CH2O \u2192 HOCH2CHO (glycolaldehyde) occurs. Borate minerals stabilize the sugar products by forming borate esters, preventing uncontrolled polymerization.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction producing glycolaldehyde from formaldehyde is a classic prebiotic chemistry pathway (Butlerow, 1861; Breslow, 1959). Borate minerals stabilize sugars and prevent tar formation (Ricardo et al., 2004). Glycolaldehyde is the simplest sugar and serves as a precursor to lactaldehyde via aldol condensation with formaldehyde. This reaction connects hydrothermal formaldehyde to surface sugar chemistry, feeding the cyanosulfidic threonine pathway (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay / borate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mildly alkaline evaporitic pools; aldol condensation extending C2 to C3"}, "mechanism": "Aldol condensation: the alpha-carbon of glycolaldehyde (HOCH2CHO) is deprotonated under basic conditions to form an enolate, which attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde. This generates a C3 aldol product, lactaldehyde (CH3CH(OH)CHO), after tautomerization/dehydration-rehydration. Clay surfaces may template the reaction and borate complexes stabilize the hydroxy aldehyde product.", "reasoning": "Lactaldehyde is identified by Patel et al. (2015) as the starting aldehyde for the cyanosulfidic threonine pathway, and could form 'from aldol chemistry of simpler aldehydes (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde).' This aldol condensation is a standard sugar chemistry transformation and is prebiotically plausible in evaporitic pools where reactants are concentrated by wet-dry cycling. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes aldol reactions on mineral surfaces (Ferris et al., 1996)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: lactaldehyde + HCN", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay surface)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Cyanosulfidic surface pool conditions; aqueous HCN; Kiliani-type cyanohydrin reaction"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the aldehyde carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde. Under mildly basic conditions, HCN deprotonates to form cyanide ion, which attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde (CH3CH(OH)CHO). Protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the cyanohydrin product, 2,3-dihydroxybutanenitrile (CH3CH(OH)CH(OH)CN). This is a classic Kiliani reaction extending the carbon chain by one unit.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry) describe this as Step 1 of the cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis: 'Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the aldehyde carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde... This is a classic Kiliani-type cyanohydrin reaction that extends the carbon chain by one carbon unit while introducing a nitrile functional group.' The reaction operates under mild aqueous conditions in cyanosulfidic surface pools."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Strecker-type amination of cyanohydrin to aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay surface)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions; Strecker-type amination; NH3 displaces alpha-OH"}, "mechanism": "Strecker-type amination: ammonia (NH3) displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile of the cyanohydrin intermediate. NH3 acts as a nucleophile, attacking the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group. The hydroxyl is displaced as water, and the carbon skeleton rearranges to yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (CH3CH(OH)CH(NH2)CN) with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine retained.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry) describe this as Step 2: 'Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water.' This operates under the same cyanosulfidic surface pool conditions and produces the direct aminonitrile precursor of threonine."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Nitrile hydrolysis of aminonitrile to L-threonine", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay surface); mild UV may accelerate", "aqueous": true, "other": "Aqueous cyanosulfidic conditions; stepwise nitrile hydrolysis via amide intermediate; 2 equivalents of H2O consumed"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis: water attacks the nitrile carbon of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide). A second water molecule hydrolyzes the amide to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of NH3. Net: CH3CH(OH)CH(NH2)CN + 2H2O \u2192 CH3CH(OH)CH(NH2)COOH + NH3. The released ammonia is recycled back into the network.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry) describe this as the terminal step: 'Nucleophilic addition of water to the nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, forming an amide intermediate... followed by further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia.' This is the general cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid conversion. NH3 is regenerated, creating a catalytic cycle for the nitrogen atom."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde to L-threonine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-500K", "pressure": "high (submarine hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "greigite / iron sulfide minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "Submarine hydrothermal vent conditions; elevated temperature and pressure drive the aldol condensation"}, "mechanism": "Aldol-type condensation: the alpha-carbon of L-alanine (adjacent to the amino and carboxyl groups) is deprotonated to form a carbanion/enolate equivalent, which attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde. This forms a new C\u2013C bond and introduces a hydroxymethyl group, extending the C3 amino acid (alanine) to the C4 amino acid (threonine). The beta-hydroxyl group characteristic of threonine is installed directly from the formaldehyde oxygen.", "reasoning": "Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008, Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres) demonstrated that 'L-alanine reacts with formaldehyde to produce L-threonine via aldol condensation' under simulated submarine hydrothermal vent conditions. This is directly analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine reaction from the same study. Iron sulfide minerals present in hydrothermal vents may facilitate the reaction by providing Lewis acid catalysis at the mineral-water interface."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Strecker synthesis of 2-aminopropanenitrile from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay surface)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Classic Strecker synthesis; cyanosulfidic surface pool conditions; acetaldehyde + HCN + NH3"}, "mechanism": "Two-step Strecker mechanism: (1) ammonia condenses with acetaldehyde to form an imine (CH3CH=NH) with loss of water, (2) cyanide ion (from HCN) adds to the imine carbon in a nucleophilic addition, yielding 2-aminopropanenitrile (CH3CH(NH2)CN). This is the classic Strecker aminonitrile synthesis producing the immediate precursor to alanine.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is a well-established prebiotic route to aminonitriles and amino acids. Patel et al. (2015) describe 'hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions' as one route to alanine. This reaction uses acetaldehyde produced by hydrothermal FTT chemistry (rxn_003), connecting hydrothermal C1/C2 fixation to surface Strecker synthesis. The same cyanosulfidic framework applies here as for the threonine-specific pathway (Miller, 1957; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile to L-alanine", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay surface); UV may assist", "aqueous": true, "other": "Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis in aqueous surface pools; analogous to rxn_010; 2 equivalents H2O consumed, NH3 released"}, "mechanism": "Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis: water attacks the nitrile carbon of 2-aminopropanenitrile, forming 2-aminopropanamide (alaninamide). Further hydrolysis of the amide yields L-alanine (CH3CH(NH2)COOH) with release of ammonia. Net: CH3CH(NH2)CN + 2H2O \u2192 CH3CH(NH2)COOH + NH3. This is the same general aminonitrile hydrolysis mechanism as rxn_010.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) identify 'hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions' as a route to alanine within the unified cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework. This is the terminal nitrile-to-amino acid conversion step of the Strecker synthesis, well established in prebiotic chemistry (Miller, 1957; Patel et al., 2015). The alanine produced here feeds into the hydrothermal aldol route (rxn_011) to threonine."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full cyanosulfidic route: CO2 \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine", "description": "Complete pathway from CO2 through hydrothermal CO/formaldehyde production, surface formose/aldol synthesis of lactaldehyde, and cyanosulfidic cyanohydrin-aminonitrile-hydrolysis sequence to threonine. This is the primary literature-supported cyanosulfidic route (Patel et al., 2015) with upstream hydrothermal C1 fixation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal aldol route via reductive amination of pyruvate", "description": "Hydrothermal pathway: CO2 is fixed to CO, then to acetaldehyde via FTT. Acetaldehyde is carboxylated to pyruvate. Pyruvate is reductively aminated with hydroxylamine on Fe\u2070 to produce alanine. Meanwhile, CO is converted to formaldehyde via FTT. Alanine + formaldehyde undergo aldol condensation to threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_002", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_015", "mol_007"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal aldol route via Strecker alanine", "description": "Hybrid hydrothermal-surface pathway: CO2 is fixed to CO and acetaldehyde via FTT (hydrothermal). Acetaldehyde is transported to surface pools where Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH3 produces 2-aminopropanenitrile, which hydrolyzes to alanine. Alanine returns to hydrothermal environment and reacts with formaldehyde (also from FTT) via aldol condensation to yield threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_002", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_012", "mol_016", "mol_015", "mol_007"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formaldehyde hub pathway to threonine via cyanosulfidic chemistry", "description": "Traces the role of formaldehyde as a central hub molecule: formaldehyde produced hydrothermally (rxn_002) enters surface chemistry where it feeds the formose reaction to glycolaldehyde (rxn_006), then aldol condensation to lactaldehyde (rxn_007), then the cyanosulfidic cyanohydrin pathway to threonine. Formaldehyde is consumed in two separate surface reactions.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Carbon monoxide as universal C1 carrier", "description": "Highlights CO as the central C1 intermediate: CO2 is reduced to CO (rxn_001), which diverges into formaldehyde (rxn_002, C1 oxygenate) and acetaldehyde (rxn_003, C2 oxygenate). Formaldehyde feeds the cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde route; acetaldehyde feeds pyruvate/alanine. Both branches ultimately converge on threonine via different final steps.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Pyruvate metabolic hub to alanine to threonine", "description": "Traces the metabolic role of pyruvate as a hub: acetaldehyde from FTT is carboxylated to pyruvate on greigite (rxn_004), pyruvate is reductively aminated to alanine on Fe\u2070 (rxn_005), and alanine undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to produce threonine (rxn_011). This pathway emphasizes proto-metabolic transformations centered on pyruvate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Strecker aminonitrile route to alanine", "description": "Surface cyanosulfidic pathway producing alanine: acetaldehyde (from hydrothermal FTT) reacts with HCN and NH3 via Strecker synthesis to form 2-aminopropanenitrile (rxn_012), which hydrolyzes to alanine (rxn_013). This alanine feeds the hydrothermal aldol condensation with formaldehyde to threonine (rxn_011). Demonstrates cross-environment flow.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_016", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Cyanosulfidic aminonitrile to threonine (core Patel et al. pathway)", "description": "The three-step core cyanosulfidic pathway from Patel et al. (2015): lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 cyanohydrin (rxn_008), cyanohydrin + NH3 \u2192 aminonitrile (rxn_009), aminonitrile hydrolysis \u2192 threonine (rxn_010). This is the experimentally demonstrated route assuming lactaldehyde is available.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Cross-environment Strecker alanine to hydrothermal threonine", "description": "Complete cross-environment pathway: CO2 is fixed hydrothermally to CO \u2192 acetaldehyde and CO \u2192 formaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is transported to surface pools for Strecker alanine synthesis. Alanine returns to hydrothermal vents where it undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to yield threonine. This demonstrates bidirectional Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface molecular flow.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_003", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_016", "mol_015", "mol_007"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Ammonia recycling through cyanosulfidic network", "description": "Traces the nitrogen cycle within the network: NH3 is consumed in rxn_009 (amination of cyanohydrin to aminonitrile) and in rxn_012 (Strecker synthesis), but is regenerated in rxn_010 (aminonitrile hydrolysis to threonine) and rxn_013 (aminopropanenitrile hydrolysis to alanine). This creates a catalytic nitrogen cycle where NH3 acts as a shuttle, enabling net conversion of nitrile groups to carboxylic acids without stoichiometric NH3 consumption across the full cycle.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_011", "mol_016"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_007", "mol_013", "mol_015"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_007", "description": "Formaldehyde \u2014 central C1 hub linking hydrothermal carbon fixation to both threonine pathways", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_015", "description": "L-Alanine \u2014 convergence of two independent synthesis routes (reductive amination of pyruvate and Strecker hydrolysis) feeding into the hydrothermal aldol pathway to threonine", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_011"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_004", "description": "Ammonia \u2014 recycled nitrogen carrier consumed in amination reactions and regenerated by nitrile hydrolysis, creating a catalytic N-cycle", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_013", "description": "Pyruvate \u2014 central alpha-keto acid metabolic hub produced by reductive carboxylation of acetaldehyde, feeding into alanine synthesis", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_017", "description": "L-Threonine \u2014 target molecule reached by two independent final-step reactions from different environments", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": []}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 477379.9569606781, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T23:53:34.764656", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: L-Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: Two experimentally demonstrated prebiotic routes converge on L-threonine: (1) a cyanosulfidic surface pathway from lactaldehyde + HCN through a cyanohydrin and aminonitrile intermediate (Patel et al., 2015), and (2) a hydrothermal aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde (Aubrey et al., 2008). Both are fed by upstream hydrothermal C1 fixation (CO2 \u2192 CO \u2192 formaldehyde, acetaldehyde) via Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on magnetite. L-Alanine itself is produced by two independent routes: reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine on Fe\u2070 (Muchowska et al., 2019) and Strecker synthesis from acetaldehyde. Formaldehyde serves as the central C1 hub linking hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface aldol and cyanosulfidic chemistry. The network is designed to avoid oversimplified single-step CO2-to-pyruvate conversions by routing through CO, acetaldehyde, and carboxylation intermediates.\n\nMOLECULES (17 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (Carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (Hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: H2O (Water) [starting]\n  - mol_004: H3N (Ammonia) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: CHN (HCN) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: CO (Carbon monoxide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_007: CH2O (Formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C2H4O2 (Glycolaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C3H6O2 (Lactaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C4H7NO2 (Lactaldehyde cyanohydrin) [intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C4H8N2O (2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C2H4O (Acetaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3H4O3 (Pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_014: NH3O (Hydroxylamine) [starting]\n  - mol_015: C3H7NO2 (L-Alanine) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C3H6N2 (2-Aminopropanenitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_017: C4H9NO3 (L-Threonine) [target]\n\nREACTIONS (13 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_006, mol_003 (Reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_006, mol_002 -> mol_007, mol_003 (Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_006, mol_002 -> mol_012, mol_003 (Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_012, mol_001 -> mol_013 (Reductive carboxylation of acetaldehyde to pyruvate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_013, mol_014 -> mol_015, mol_003 (Reductive amination of pyruvate to L-alanine) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_006: mol_007 -> mol_008 (Formose-type dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_008, mol_007 -> mol_009 (Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde with formaldehyde to lactaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_009, mol_005 -> mol_010 (Cyanohydrin formation: lactaldehyde + HCN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_010, mol_004 -> mol_011, mol_003 (Strecker-type amination of cyanohydrin to aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_011, mol_003 -> mol_017, mol_004 (Nitrile hydrolysis of aminonitrile to L-threonine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_015, mol_007 -> mol_017 (Aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde to L-threonine) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_012: mol_012, mol_005, mol_004 -> mol_016, mol_003 (Strecker synthesis of 2-aminopropanenitrile from acetaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_016, mol_003 -> mol_015, mol_004 (Hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile to L-alanine) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Full cyanosulfidic route: CO2 \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 lactaldehyde \u2192 threonine (7 steps)\n  - P2: Hydrothermal aldol route via reductive amination of pyruvate (6 steps)\n  - P3: Hydrothermal aldol route via Strecker alanine (6 steps)\n  - P4: Formaldehyde hub pathway to threonine via cyanosulfidic chemistry (6 steps)\n  - P5: Carbon monoxide as universal C1 carrier (3 steps)\n  - P6: Pyruvate metabolic hub to alanine to threonine (3 steps)\n  - P7: Strecker aminonitrile route to alanine (3 steps)\n  - P8: Cyanosulfidic aminonitrile to threonine (core Patel et al. pathway) (3 steps)\n  - P9: Cross-environment Strecker alanine to hydrothermal threonine (7 steps)\n  - P10: Ammonia recycling through cyanosulfidic network (4 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_004, mol_005, mol_007, mol_013, mol_015\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n# Prebiotic Synthesis of L-Threonine: Comprehensive Literature Review\n\n## 1. Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\n\nTwo experimentally demonstrated pathways produce L-threonine (C4H9NO3, SMILES: CC(C(C(=O)O)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8), MW: 119.12) from prebiotically available precursors. These span surface and hydrothermal environments.\n\n### Pathway 1: Cyanosulfidic Nitrile Hydrolysis via Lactaldehyde Cyanohydrin (Surface Environment)\n\nThe cyanosulfidic protometabolism pathway demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) constructs L-threonine through a 3-step sequence starting from **lactaldehyde** and **hydrogen cyanide**, proceeding through a cyanohydrin intermediate and an aminonitrile intermediate. This pathway follows the general cyanosulfidic strategy: an aldehyde undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN, amination with ammonia displaces the hydroxyl to form an aminonitrile, and final nitrile hydrolysis yields the amino acid.\n\n**Step 1**: Lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 Cyanohydrin intermediate (Cyanohydrin formation)\n- SMILES: CC(O)C=O.C#N>>CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- Reactants: Lactaldehyde (C3H6O2, SMILES: CC(C=O)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3, MW: 74.08) + Hydrogen cyanide (CHN, SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H, MW: 27.03)\n- Product: Cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2, SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c1-4(7)2-5(8)3-6/h4-5,7-8H,2H2,1H3, MW: 115.06)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the aldehyde carbonyl carbon of lactaldehyde. The cyanide ion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of the aldehyde, and subsequent protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani-type cyanohydrin reaction that extends the carbon chain by one carbon unit while introducing a nitrile functional group. Lactaldehyde is a plausible prebiotic C3 aldol product available from cyanosulfidic chemistry.\n\n**Step 2**: Cyanohydrin intermediate + NH3 \u2192 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + H2O (Aminonitrile formation)\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N.N>>CC(O)C(N)C#N.O\n- Reactants: Cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2, SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N) + Ammonia (H3N, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3, MW: 17.03)\n- Products: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3, MW: 100.12) + H2O (SMILES: O)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement of the carbon skeleton to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.\n\n**Step 3**: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Threonine + NH3 (Nitrile hydrolysis)\n- SMILES: CC(O)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(O)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Reactants: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O, SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O) + 2 H2O (SMILES: O)\n- Products: L-Threonine (C4H9NO3, SMILES: CC(C(C(=O)O)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8), MW: 119.12) + Ammonia (H3N, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3)\n- Environment: Surface (evaporitic pools, cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of water to the nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide), followed by further hydrolysis to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia (NH3). This is the final step of the general cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid pathway, converting the C\u2261N triple bond to a carboxylic acid via stepwise hydration.\n\nThis three-step sequence is part of the broader Powell-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry framework, in which HCN-derived nitriles serve as amino acid precursors via hydrolysis under wet-dry cycling or UV-irradiated surface pool conditions. The same paper demonstrates that this unified chemistry produces precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids from simple feedstocks. The threonine pathway parallels the serine pathway (glycolaldehyde + HCN) but uses lactaldehyde as the starting aldehyde, introducing the methyl branch that distinguishes threonine from serine.\n\n### Pathway 2: Aldol Condensation of L-Alanine with Formaldehyde (Hydrothermal Environment)\n\nAubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, DOI: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2) demonstrated that **L-alanine** (C3H7NO2, SMILES: CC(C(=O)O)N, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6), MW: 89.09) reacts with **formaldehyde** (CH2O, SMILES: C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2, MW: 30.03) to produce L-threonine under submarine hydrothermal conditions.\n\n**Reaction**: L-Alanine + Formaldehyde \u2192 L-Threonine\n- SMILES: C[C@H](N)C(=O)O.C=O>>C[C@@H](O)[C@H](N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Hydrothermal (submarine hydrothermal systems)\n- Conditions: Elevated temperature and pressure characteristic of submarine hydrothermal vents\n- Mechanism: Aldol-type condensation \u2014 the alpha-carbon of L-alanine attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a hydroxymethyl group (-CH(OH)-). This converts the C3 amino acid (alanine) into the C4 amino acid (threonine) by extending the carbon skeleton by one carbon unit. Formaldehyde is a key C1 electrophile that is abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids from reduction of CO2 and Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry.\n\nThis pathway links threonine synthesis to L-alanine, which is itself produced by multiple prebiotic routes including: (a) reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine in the presence of iron (Muchowska et al., 2019), (b) hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015), and (c) reduction of L-serine under hydrothermal conditions (Aubrey et al., 2008). The reaction is directly analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation demonstrated by the same research group, but applied one carbon unit higher in the amino acid homologous series.\n\n## 2. Key Intermediates and Precursors\n\n### Hub Molecule: L-Alanine (C3H7NO2)\n- Formula: C3H7NO2\n- SMILES: CC(C(=O)O)N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\n- MW: 89.09\n- Role: **Key amino acid precursor for Pathway 2** \u2014 L-alanine is the substrate for the aldol condensation with formaldehyde that produces threonine (Aubrey et al., 2008). Alanine is itself produced by multiple prebiotic routes: reductive amination of pyruvate with hydroxylamine using iron catalysts at 70\u00b0C (Muchowska et al., 2019), hydrolysis of 2-aminopropanenitrile under cyanosulfidic conditions (Patel et al., 2015), and reduction of L-serine under hydrothermal conditions (Aubrey et al., 2008). Alanine is one of the most abundant amino acids produced in prebiotic chemistry experiments.\n\n### Key Intermediate: Cyanohydrin Intermediate (C5H9NO2)\n- Formula: C5H9NO2\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c1-4(7)2-5(8)3-6/h4-5,7-8H,2H2,1H3\n- MW: 115.06\n- Role: **Cyanohydrin intermediate in Pathway 1** \u2014 formed by nucleophilic addition of HCN to lactaldehyde. This intermediate is the direct precursor to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile via amination with ammonia. Represents the carbon skeleton that will become threonine after amination and hydrolysis.\n\n### Key Intermediate: 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O)\n- Formula: C4H8N2O\n- SMILES: CC(C(C#N)N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\n- MW: 100.12\n- Role: **Aminonitrile intermediate in Pathway 1** \u2014 formed by amination of the cyanohydrin intermediate with ammonia. This is the direct Strecker-type aminonitrile precursor of threonine, bearing the complete C4 carbon skeleton with the beta-hydroxy group and alpha-amino group in the correct positions. Hydrolysis of the nitrile group yields threonine.\n\n### Other Key Molecules\n\n**Lactaldehyde** (C3H6O2)\n- Formula: C3H6O2\n- SMILES: CC(C=O)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3\n- MW: 74.08\n- Role: Starting aldehyde for Pathway 1 \u2014 undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN to initiate the cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis. Lactaldehyde is a C3 hydroxy aldehyde that is prebiotically plausible as a product of aldol chemistry and sugar photochemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions.\n\n**Hydrogen Cyanide** (CHN)\n- Formula: CHN\n- SMILES: C#N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- MW: 27.03\n- Role: Key C1 nucleophile for cyanohydrin formation in Pathway 1. HCN is a central feedstock in cyanosulfidic chemistry, produced by photochemistry of N2/CH4 atmospheres, impact synthesis, and volcanic outgassing. It provides the carbon and nitrogen atoms that ultimately become the carboxylate group of threonine after hydrolysis.\n\n**Formaldehyde** (CH2O)\n- Formula: CH2O\n- SMILES: C=O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\n- MW: 30.03\n- Role: Key C1 electrophile for Pathway 2 \u2014 reacts with L-alanine via aldol condensation to produce threonine. Formaldehyde is a common prebiotic starting molecule produced by photoreduction of CO2, hydrothermal reduction of CO2, Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on mineral surfaces, and UV photolysis of methane.\n\n### Starting Molecules\n- **H2O**: SMILES: O, InChI: InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\n- **NH3** (ammonia): SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\n- **HCN** (hydrogen cyanide): SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- **H2CO** (formaldehyde): SMILES: C=O, InChI: InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\n\n## 3. Reaction Mechanisms and Conditions\n\n### Reactions Producing Intermediates (Upstream)\n\n**Reaction U1: HCN cyanohydrin addition to lactaldehyde**\n- Lactaldehyde + HCN \u2192 Cyanohydrin intermediate\n- SMILES: CC(O)C=O.C#N>>CC(O)CC(O)C#N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the aldehyde carbonyl of lactaldehyde, forming a cyanohydrin. This is a classic Kiliani reaction that extends the carbon chain by one unit. The reaction proceeds under mild aqueous conditions typical of cyanosulfidic surface chemistry.\n\n**Reaction U2: Aminonitrile formation from cyanohydrin + ammonia**\n- Cyanohydrin intermediate + NH3 \u2192 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + H2O\n- SMILES: CC(O)CC(O)C#N.N>>CC(O)C(N)C#N.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Strecker-type amination \u2014 ammonia displaces the hydroxyl group at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile, converting the cyanohydrin to an aminonitrile with release of water. The reaction involves nucleophilic attack of NH3 on the carbon bearing the hydroxyl group, with rearrangement of the carbon skeleton to yield the C4 aminonitrile with the beta-hydroxy group characteristic of threonine.\n\n### Reactions Producing L-Threonine (Final Steps)\n\n**Reaction F1: Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile**\n- 2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Threonine + NH3\n- SMILES: CC(O)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(O)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Conditions: Aqueous, ambient temperature and pressure\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Stepwise nitrile hydrolysis \u2014 water attacks the nitrile carbon, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanamide), which further hydrolyzes to the carboxylic acid (threonine) with release of ammonia. This is the terminal step of the general Strecker/cyanosulfidic aminonitrile-to-amino acid conversion.\n\n**Reaction F2: Aldol condensation of L-alanine with formaldehyde**\n- L-Alanine + Formaldehyde \u2192 L-Threonine\n- SMILES: C[C@H](N)C(=O)O.C=O>>C[C@@H](O)[C@H](N)C(=O)O\n- Environment: Hydrothermal (submarine hydrothermal systems)\n- Conditions: Elevated temperature and pressure\n- Source: Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008), *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, DOI: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2\n- Mechanism: Aldol condensation \u2014 the alpha-carbon of L-alanine attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde, forming a new C\u2013C bond and introducing a beta-hydroxyl group. This extends the C3 amino acid (alanine) to the C4 amino acid (threonine). The reaction is analogous to the glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation from the same study.\n\n## 4. Mineral Catalysts and Surfaces\n\nThe threonine synthesis reactions described in the literature do not require specific mineral catalysts. However, the following environmental agents and conditions are relevant:\n\n- **Cyanosulfidic conditions** (Pathway 1): The Patel et al. (2015) reactions operate under the cyanosulfidic chemistry framework, which involves hydrogen cyanide (HCN), hydrogen sulfide (H2S), and UV irradiation in surface pools. While no specific mineral catalysts are documented for the threonine-specific reactions, the broader cyanosulfidic network utilizes phosphate minerals for phosphorylation and UV light as an energy source.\n\n- **Hydrothermal mineral surfaces** (Pathway 2): The Aubrey et al. (2008) aldol condensation operates under submarine hydrothermal conditions. While no specific mineral catalyst is documented for the alanine-formaldehyde condensation itself, the hydrothermal environment provides elevated temperatures and mineral surfaces (e.g., iron-sulfide minerals, clay minerals) that may facilitate the reaction. Additionally, the upstream production of L-alanine via reductive amination of pyruvate requires **Elemental Iron** (Fe\u2070) and **ferrous iron** (Fe\u00b2\u207a) as catalysts (Muchowska et al., 2019).\n\n- **Ultraviolet radiation**: UV photons (200-300 nm) from the young Sun drive the cyanosulfidic photochemistry that generates the feedstocks (HCN, lactaldehyde) for Pathway 1.\n\n## 5. Experimental Evidence\n\n### Study 1: Patel et al. (2015)\n- **Title**: \"Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism\"\n- **Journal**: Nature Chemistry\n- **DOI**: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- **Key finding**: Demonstrated that a unified cyanosulfidic chemistry starting from HCN and H2S can produce precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids. For threonine specifically, the paper describes a three-step pathway: (1) HCN cyanohydrin addition to lactaldehyde produces a cyanohydrin intermediate (C5H9NO2), (2) amination with ammonia converts the cyanohydrin to 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (C4H8N2O), and (3) nitrile hydrolysis yields L-threonine with release of ammonia. This is the cyanosulfidic analog of the Strecker synthesis, where the starting aldehyde (lactaldehyde) determines the amino acid product (threonine). The same framework produces glycine (from formaldehyde), alanine (from acetaldehyde), serine (from glycolaldehyde), and valine (from dihydroxyacetone-derived acetone), demonstrating a unified chemical origin for the amino acid repertoire.\n\n### Study 2: Aubrey, Cleaves, and Bada (2008)\n- **Title**: \"The Role of Submarine Hydrothermal Systems in the Synthesis of Amino Acids\"\n- **Journal**: Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres\n- **DOI**: 10.1007/s11084-008-9153-2\n- **Key finding**: Investigated amino acid synthesis under simulated submarine hydrothermal vent conditions. Demonstrated that L-alanine reacts with formaldehyde to produce L-threonine via aldol condensation. This reaction extends the carbon skeleton of a simpler amino acid (alanine, C3) to a more complex one (threonine, C4) by incorporating a C1 unit (formaldehyde). The same study demonstrated the analogous glycine + formaldehyde \u2192 serine aldol condensation, as well as serine reduction to alanine. These reactions establish a hydrothermal amino acid interconversion network where simpler amino acids serve as building blocks for more complex ones through aldol chemistry with formaldehyde.\n\n## 6. Environmental Context\n\n### Surface Environment (Primary for Pathway 1)\nThe cyanosulfidic threonine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015) operates under surface conditions:\n- **Cyanosulfidic nitrile chemistry**: Lactaldehyde reacts with HCN to form a cyanohydrin, which is aminated by ammonia and then hydrolyzed to threonine. This operates in surface pools where HCN-derived chemistry (UV-driven, evaporitic) produces aminonitrile intermediates that hydrolyze in wet phases.\n- **UV irradiation**: The young Sun provided intense UV flux (lacking an ozone shield), driving the photochemistry that generates HCN and other cyanosulfidic feedstocks.\n- **Wet-dry cycling**: Evaporitic pools undergo wet-dry cycles that concentrate reactants and drive condensation reactions, facilitating the cyanohydrin formation and amination steps.\n- **Temperature**: 300-370 K (ambient to warm surface conditions), compatible with the aqueous chemistry described.\n\n### Hydrothermal Environment (Primary for Pathway 2)\nThe aldol condensation pathway (Aubrey et al., 2008) operates under submarine hydrothermal conditions:\n- **L-Alanine availability**: L-alanine is produced by iron-catalyzed reductive amination of pyruvate at 70\u00b0C (Muchowska et al., 2019), by reduction of L-serine (Aubrey et al., 2008), and by cyanosulfidic aminonitrile hydrolysis (Patel et al., 2015). Multiple upstream pathways feed alanine into the hydrothermal environment.\n- **Formaldehyde availability**: Formaldehyde is produced by hydrothermal reduction of CO2 and by Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on native iron and nickel-iron mineral surfaces. It is a key C1 building block abundantly available in hydrothermal vent fluids.\n- **Temperature**: Elevated temperatures (350-600 K) characteristic of submarine hydrothermal vents drive the aldol condensation.\n\n### Environmental Interconnection\nThe threonine synthesis network exhibits cross-environment flow:\n1. **Surface \u2192 Hydrothermal**: L-Alanine produced by cyanosulfidic chemistry (Pathway 1-type aminonitrile hydrolysis in surface pools) could be transported to hydrothermal environments, where it undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde (Pathway 2).\n2. **Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface**: Alanine and formaldehyde generated at hydrothermal vents could be transported to surface environments via ocean circulation.\n3. **Parallel independent routes**: The two pathways operate independently in different environments (surface cyanosulfidic vs. hydrothermal aldol), providing robustness to the prebiotic threonine synthesis network.\n4. **Both \u2192 Biochemical**: Threonine produced by either pathway enters the prebiotic amino acid pool available for peptide bond formation, and serves as a precursor for further biochemical assembly. Threonine itself can thermally decompose to glycine under hydrothermal conditions (Vallentyne, 1964; Bada et al., 1978), linking it to the broader amino acid recycling network.\n\n## 7. Open Questions and Challenges\n\n1. **Chirality**: Both demonstrated prebiotic routes produce racemic threonine (equal L and D forms). The origin of homochirality (biological preference for L-amino acids) remains unresolved. Mineral surface adsorption, photolysis with circularly polarized light, or amplification through autocatalytic crystallization have been proposed but not demonstrated specifically for threonine.\n\n2. **Lactaldehyde availability**: Pathway 1 requires lactaldehyde (2-hydroxypropionaldehyde), whose prebiotic abundance and stability are debated. It could form from aldol chemistry of simpler aldehydes (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde), from sugar photochemistry under cyanosulfidic conditions, or from reduction of pyruvaldehyde. Quantitative constraints on its steady-state concentration in surface environments are needed.\n\n3. **Threonine thermal stability**: Threonine is thermally labile and decomposes to glycine under hydrothermal conditions (Vallentyne, 1964; Bada et al., 1978). The balance between threonine production (via aldol condensation, Pathway 2) and thermal decomposition at hydrothermal temperatures is a key kinetic question. The retro-aldol decomposition of threonine to glycine (the reverse of the serine-type aldol reaction) may limit threonine accumulation in hydrothermal systems.\n\n4. **2-Amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile stability**: Pathway 1 requires this aminonitrile intermediate to persist long enough for hydrolysis. Its stability under UV irradiation, varying pH, and temperature fluctuations in surface pools needs further study. Competing reactions (polymerization, reaction with other HCN-derived species) could reduce yields.\n\n5. **Formaldehyde concentration**: Pathway 2 requires formaldehyde, which is volatile and reactive. Its prebiotic concentration in hydrothermal environments is debated. Mineral adsorption, continuous production from CO2 reduction via serpentinization-derived H2, and thermophoretic concentration may maintain sufficient steady-state levels.\n\n6. **Alanine as precursor**: Pathway 2 requires L-alanine as a substrate, which must itself be produced by upstream prebiotic reactions. The availability of alanine in sufficient concentrations at hydrothermal vents, where it is simultaneously being consumed by aldol condensation and potentially decomposed at high temperatures, represents a kinetic bottleneck that needs quantitative modeling.\n\n7. **Selectivity and side products**: The aldol condensation of alanine with formaldehyde (Pathway 2) could potentially produce other isomeric products besides threonine. The stereoselectivity and regioselectivity of this reaction under prebiotic conditions, and the relative yields of threonine versus allo-threonine or other isomers, need further characterization.\n\n=== END CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    